{"title_page": "Carlson Wade", "text_new": "{{short description|American alternative health writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Carlson Wade\n| image      = Carlson Wade author.png\n|birth_date  = 1928\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = 1993\n|death_place = \n| occupation = Alternative health writer}}\n\n'''Carlson Wade''' (1928-1993) was an American [[Alternative medicine|alternative health]] writer who authored many books promoting [[Detoxification (alternative medicine)|detoxification]], [[fasting]], [[juicing]], [[natural foods]] and [[Raw foodism|raw food]] dieting. He developed a [[fad diet]] known as the Enzyme-Catalyst Diet. \n\n==Biography==\n\nWade first became known for his books on sexual topics such as [[fetishism]], [[homosexuality]], [[sadomasochism]] and [[transvestism]]. His ''The Trouble Sex'', published in 1961 offered behavioral clues how the American public could \"detect\" a [[lesbian]].<ref>Caramagno, Thomas C. (2002). ''Irreconcilable Differences?: Intellectual Stalemate in the Gay Rights Debate''. Praeger. p. 85. {{ISBN|0-275-97711-0}}</ref> His work was classified as \"pulp sexology\", for example his book ''Sexual Deviations of the American Female'' (1965) gave anthropological generalisations about lesbian subcultures.<ref>Heike Bauer, Matt Cook. (2012). ''Queer 1950s: Rethinking Sexuality in the Postwar Years''. Palgrave. p. 161. {{ISBN|978-0-230-30069-9}}</ref> \n\nWade's books on dieting and health were criticized by medical experts as [[quackery]]. His ''The New Enzyme-Catalyst Diet'' (1976), recommended with each meal to add raw fruit and vegetables such as [[banana]]s, [[celery]], [[Nut (food)|nut]]s and [[wheat germ]].<ref name=\"Stern 1979\">Stern, Judith S; Nussen-Kane, Bryna. (1979). ''Obesity: Its Assessment, Risks and Treatment''. In Robert E. Hodges. (1979). ''Nutrition: Metabolic and Clinical Applications''. Plenum Press. pp. 372-273. {{ISBN|978-1-4615-7215-2}}</ref> \n\nThe diet forbid the consumption of fried, processed or sugar foods.<ref name=\"Hearing 1984\">[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031883351&view=1up&seq=259 ''Nutrition Education and Training of Health Professionals Hearing Before the Subcommittee on Domestic Marketing, Consumer Relations, and Nutrition of the Committee on Agriculture, House of Representatives, Ninety-eighth Congress, first session, November 10, 1983'']. U.S. Government Printing Office, 1984.</ref> Wade argued that raw fruits and vegetables \"are prime sources of enzymes which then are used by your billions of body cells to alert the mitochondria to perform internal combustion; this action helps to melt the accumulated fat in your cells, and wash them right out of your body.\"<ref name=\"Hearing 1984\" /> This idea is not supported by scientific evidence.<ref name=\"Hearing 1984\" /><ref>Newmark, Stephen R; Williamson, Beverly. (1983). ''Survey of Very-Low-Calorie Weight Reduction Diets I. Novelty Diets''. ''[[Archives of Internal Medicine]]'' 143: (6):1195-1198</ref> \n\nDieticians noted that the statement is false because enzymes in foods are digested to amino acids and once absorbed play no enzymatic role.<ref>Crosser, Gail Hoddlebrink. (1985). [https://archive.org/details/ERIC_ED321998/page/n13 ''Nutrition in Health Promotion: Decoding Fad Diets'']. U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. pp. 18-19</ref>\n\nNutritionist [[Judith S. Stern]] commented that Wade's ''The New Enzyme-Catalyst Diet'' is filled with scientific misstatements such as \"the most vital digestive enzyme is hydrochloric acid\" and concluded that it is a \"classroom example of a fad diet.\"<ref name=\"Stern 1979\"/>\n\nWade's book ''Health Food Recipes for Gourmet Cooking'', was criticized by ''[[Choice Reviews]]'' as \"unintelligible jargon at best\".<ref>Kaplan, Doris Flax. (1974). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NwE9AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA888&dq=carlson+wade+nutrition&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiRit2C39nmAhXTbsAKHed5CYs4FBC7BQgqMAA#v=onepage&q=carlson%20wade%20nutrition&f=false ''Foods and Faddists: A Guide to Popular Books on Cooking and Diets'']. ''[[Choice Reviews|Choice: Publication of the Association of College and Research Libraries]]''. Volume 11, Issue 7. p. 888</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{collist|\n*''Erotic Symbolism'' (1960, with Edward Podolsky)\n*[https://archive.org/details/SexualMasochismTheSexualPleasureOfPain ''Sexual Masochism''] (1960, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''Transvestism Today'' (1960, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''Sexual Sadism'' (1961, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''The Key to Nutrition'' (1961)\n*''The Troubled Sex'' (1961)\n*[https://archive.org/details/Fetichism-SexualNatureOfEroticSymbolism ''Fetichism - Sexual Nature of Erotic Symbolism''] (1962, with Edward Podolsky)\n*[https://archive.org/details/Sadism ''Sadism''] (1963, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''The Twilight Sex'' (1964)\n*''Sexual Deviations of the American Female'' (1965)\n*''The Sexual Variants'' (1965)\n*''Male Homosexuality: A Case Study'' (1965)\n*''Sexual Deviations of the American Female'' (1965)\n*''Helping Your Health with Enzymes'' (1966)\n*''Queer Path'' (1967)\n*''Encyclopedia Erotica Sexualia'' (1967, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''Instant Health the Nature Way'' (1968)\n*''The Natural Way to Health Through Controlled Fasting'' (1968)\n*''Health Food Recipes for Gourmet Cooking'' (1969)\n*''Natural and Folk Remedies'' (1970)\n*''Health Secrets from the Orient'' (1973)\n*''Natural Hormones: The Secret of Youthful Health'' (1973)\n*''All Natural Pain Relievers'' (1975)\n*''Miracle Protein: Secret of Natural Cell-Tissue Rejuvenation'' (1976)\n*''The Miracle of Organic Vitamins for Better Health'' (1976)\n*''The New Enzyme-Catalyst Diet'' (1976)\n*''Bee Pollen and Your Health'' (1978)\n*''Lecithin Book'' (1980)\n*''Encyclopedia of Power Foods for Health and Longer Life'' (1980)\n*''Catalytic Hormones: Key to Extraordinary Weight Loss'' (1982)\n*''Inner Cleansing'' (1983)\n*''Carlson Wade's Amino Acids Book'' (1985)\n*''Nutritional Healers: How to Eat Your Way to Better Health'' (1987)\n*''Immune Power Boosters'' (1989)\n*''Bible Healing Foods'' (1990)\n*''Eat Away Illness'' (1992)\n*''The Pocket Handbook of Juice Power'' (1992)\n*''Health from The Hive<ref>ISBN 0-87983-581-8</ref>'' (1992)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://archive.org/search.php?query=creator%3A%22Wade%2C+Carlson%22 Carlson Wade at Internet Archive] \n\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Alternative detoxification promoters]]\n[[Category:Fasting advocates]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Raw foodists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American alternative health writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Carlson Wade\n| image      = Carlson Wade author.png\n|birth_date  = 1928\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = 1993\n|death_place = \n| occupation = Alternative health writer}}\n\n'''Carlson Wade''' (1928-1993) was an American [[Alternative medicine|alternative health]] writer who authored many books promoting [[Detoxification (alternative medicine)|detoxification]], [[fasting]], [[juicing]], [[natural foods]] and [[Raw foodism|raw food]] dieting. He developed a [[fad diet]] known as the Enzyme-Catalyst Diet. \n\n==Biography==\n\nWade first became known for his books on sexual topics such as [[fetishism]], [[homosexuality]], [[sadomasochism]] and [[transvestism]]. His ''The Trouble Sex'', published in 1961 offered behavioral clues how the American public could \"detect\" a [[lesbian]].<ref>Caramagno, Thomas C. (2002). ''Irreconcilable Differences?: Intellectual Stalemate in the Gay Rights Debate''. Praeger. p. 85. {{ISBN|0-275-97711-0}}</ref> His work was classified as \"pulp sexology\", for example his book ''Sexual Deviations of the American Female'' (1965) gave anthropological generalisations about lesbian subcultures.<ref>Heike Bauer, Matt Cook. (2012). ''Queer 1950s: Rethinking Sexuality in the Postwar Years''. Palgrave. p. 161. {{ISBN|978-0-230-30069-9}}</ref> \n\nWade's books on dieting and health were criticized by medical experts as [[quackery]]. His ''The New Enzyme-Catalyst Diet'' (1976), recommended with each meal to add raw fruit and vegetables such as [[banana]]s, [[celery]], [[Nut (food)|nut]]s and [[wheat germ]].<ref name=\"Stern 1979\">Stern, Judith S; Nussen-Kane, Bryna. (1979). ''Obesity: Its Assessment, Risks and Treatment''. In Robert E. Hodges. (1979). ''Nutrition: Metabolic and Clinical Applications''. Plenum Press. pp. 372-273. {{ISBN|978-1-4615-7215-2}}</ref> The diet forbid the consumption of fried, processed or sugar foods.<ref name=\"Hearing 1984\">[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015031883351&view=1up&seq=259 ''Nutrition Education and Training of Health Professionals Hearing Before the Subcommittee on Domestic Marketing, Consumer Relations, and Nutrition of the Committee on Agriculture, House of Representatives, Ninety-eighth Congress, first session, November 10, 1983'']. U.S. Government Printing Office, 1984.</ref> Wade argued that raw fruits and vegetables \"are prime sources of enzymes which then are used by your billions of body cells to alert the mitochondria to perform internal combustion; this action helps to melt the accumulated fat in your cells, and wash them right out of your body.\"<ref name=\"Hearing 1984\"/> This idea is not supported by scientific evidence.<ref name=\"Hearing 1984\"/><ref>Newmark, Stephen R; Williamson, Beverly. (1983). ''Survey of Very-Low-Calorie Weight Reduction Diets I. Novelty Diets''. ''[[Archives of Internal Medicine]]'' 143: (6):1195-1198</ref> Dieticians noted that the statement is false because enzymes in foods are digested to amino acids and once absorbed play no enzymatic role.<ref>Crosser, Gail Hoddlebrink. (1985). [https://archive.org/details/ERIC_ED321998/page/n13 ''Nutrition in Health Promotion: Decoding Fad Diets'']. U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. pp. 18-19</ref>\n\nNutritionist [[Judith S. Stern]] commented that Wade's ''The New Enzyme-Catalyst Diet'' is filled with scientific misstatements such as \"the most vital digestive enzyme is hydrochloric acid\" and concluded that it is a \"classroom example of a fad diet.\"<ref name=\"Stern 1979\"/>\n\nWade's book ''Health Food Recipes for Gourmet Cooking'', was criticized by ''[[Choice Reviews]]'' as \"unintelligible jargon at best\".<ref>Kaplan, Doris Flax. (1974). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NwE9AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA888&dq=carlson+wade+nutrition&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiRit2C39nmAhXTbsAKHed5CYs4FBC7BQgqMAA#v=onepage&q=carlson%20wade%20nutrition&f=false ''Foods and Faddists: A Guide to Popular Books on Cooking and Diets'']. ''[[Choice Reviews|Choice: Publication of the Association of College and Research Libraries]]''. Volume 11, Issue 7. p. 888</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{collist|\n*''Erotic Symbolism'' (1960, with Edward Podolsky)\n*[https://archive.org/details/SexualMasochismTheSexualPleasureOfPain ''Sexual Masochism''] (1960, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''Transvestism Today'' (1960, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''Sexual Sadism'' (1961, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''The Key to Nutrition'' (1961)\n*''The Troubled Sex'' (1961)\n*[https://archive.org/details/Fetichism-SexualNatureOfEroticSymbolism ''Fetichism - Sexual Nature of Erotic Symbolism''] (1962, with Edward Podolsky)\n*[https://archive.org/details/Sadism ''Sadism''] (1963, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''The Twilight Sex'' (1964)\n*''Sexual Deviations of the American Female'' (1965)\n*''The Sexual Variants'' (1965)\n*''Male Homosexuality: A Case Study'' (1965)\n*''Sexual Deviations of the American Female'' (1965)\n*''Helping Your Health with Enzymes'' (1966)\n*''Queer Path'' (1967)\n*''Encyclopedia Erotica Sexualia'' (1967, with Edward Podolsky)\n*''Instant Health the Nature Way'' (1968)\n*''The Natural Way to Health Through Controlled Fasting'' (1968)\n*''Health Food Recipes for Gourmet Cooking'' (1969)\