1945: An International History'']. p.535. 2nd edition. Authors - P. M. H. Bell and Mark Gilbert. Published by Bloomsbury in London. First published in 2001, 2nd edition in 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/chaos-in-parliament-as-party-gets-ejected-for-grilling-zuma-over-corruption-in-south-africa-10043286.html Chaos in parliament as party gets ejected for grilling Zuma over corruption in South Africa]. ''Independent''. Author - Lamiat Sabin. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201408222154-0024098 South African lawmakers disrupt parliament and demand Zuma #PayBackTheMoney]. ''AlJazeera''. Published 22 August 2014. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/world/266026/south-african-parliament-descends-into-chaos South African parliament descends into chaos]. ''Radio New Zealand''. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref>}}\n|international=\n|colours=[[Red]]<ref name=\"aji\"/><ref name=\"n24i\"/><ref name=\"dmi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|title=Red Tide: From 'economic freedom' to 'white genocide', extremism grabs the spotlight (in English)|publisher=[[Daily Maverick]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017020415/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|slogan=\"People\u2019s Power for Economic Freedom in Our Lifetime\"\n|seats1_title=[[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]]\n|seats1={{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats2_title=[[National Council of Provinces]]\n|seats2={{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats3_title={{nowrap|[[Pan-African Parliament]]}}\n|seats3={{Composition bar|1|5|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}<small>(South African seats)</small>\n|seats4_title=[[Provincial legislature (South Africa)|Provincial Legislatures]]\n|seats4={{Composition bar|50|430|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats5_title=[[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n|seats5={{Composition bar|30|270|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats6_title=[[Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n|seats6={{Composition bar|6|120|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats7_title=[[City of Cape Town]] (council)\n|seats7={{Composition bar|7|231|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|flag=\n|website={{Official URL}}\n|country=South Africa}}\nThe '''Economic Freedom Fighters''' ('''EFF''') is a [[South Africa]]n [[Far-left politics|far-left]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/southAfricaNews/idAFL5N1V80N0|title=South Africa's opposition EFF introduces bill to nationalise...|date=2018-08-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-23|language=en}}</ref> [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-Africanist]] [[political party]]. It was founded by expelled former [[African National Congress Youth League]] (ANCYL) President [[Julius Malema]], and his allies, in 2013.<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite news|title=Malema launches his Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Meggan Saville|url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|newspaper=Dispatch Online|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725200305/http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|archivedate=25 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Malema is President of the EFF, heading the Central Command Team which serves as the central structure of the party.<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite news|title=Malema takes command of Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Setumo Stone|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|newspaper=[[Business Day (South Africa)|Business Day]]|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130714113641/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|archivedate=14 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt is currently the third-largest party in both houses of the [[Parliament of South Africa|South African Parliament]].\n\n==History==\nAt a 26 July 2013 press briefing in [[Soweto]], Malema announced that the new party had over 1000 members, double the 500 required for registration with the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] (IEC).<ref name=\"EFF 1000\">{{cite news|title=EFF readies for election registration as over 1 000 members recruited|author=SAPA|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|newspaper=[[The Times (South Africa)|The Times]]|date=28 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730092849/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|archivedate=30 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The EFF is now registered with the IEC, after an objection to its registration by the [[Freedom Front Plus]] (FF+) was dismissed in September 2013.<ref name=\"It'sOfficial\">{{cite news|title=It's official: Malema's EFF is a political party|author=Verashni Pillay|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]|date=5 September 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907063401/http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|archivedate=7 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Splinters and infighting==\nIn 2015, the EFF suspended [[Member of parliament|MP]] Lucky Twala and expelled three MPs, Mpho Ramakatsa, Andile Mngxitama and [[Khanyisile Litchfield-Tshabalala]].<ref name=m.news24.com>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|title=Litchfield-Tshabalala UDM's new national organiser|author=Genevieve Quintal|date=2015-06-05|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930022925/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|archivedate=30 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mngxitama formed his own party, named [[Black First Land First]] (BLF), while Litchfield-Tshabalala joined the [[United Democratic Movement]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\nMalema has been chiefly accused by former members of purging his critics to consolidate his power, thus ruling the party with an iron fist. Malema acknowledged this criticism in a press conference and further went on to say, the party should have expelled more ill disciplined members.\n\n==Policies==\n[[File:EFF land march on Mandela Day 2014.JPG|thumb|A small march by the EFF on Mandela Day (18 July) 2014 near the parliament building in [[Cape Town]] protesting in support of [[land reform in South Africa]].]]\nThe EFF \"draws inspiration from the broad [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] tradition and [[Frantz Fanon|Fanonian]] schools of thought in their analyses of the state, imperialism, culture and class contradictions in every society\", according to one of its declarations.<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/declaration|title=Declaration|work=effonline.org}}</ref>\n\nIt criticises the [[African National Congress]] and their primary opposition, the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], for their allegedly pro-business stances, which it claims have sold out the black people of South Africa to capitalism as cheap labour. It promises to tackle corruption, provide quality social housing, and provide free primary healthcare and education for all, as well as proposing to [[expropriation|expropriate]] stolen land, nationalise the mining and banking sectors, double welfare grants and the minimum wage, and end the proposed toll system for highways.<ref name=\"irishtimes\"/>\n\nThe EFF takes significant inspiration from [[Thomas Sankara]] in terms of both style and ideology.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|last=Duval Smith|first=Alex|date=30 April 2014|title='Africa's Che Guevara': Thomas Sankara's legacy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|newspaper=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=[[London]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101053949/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|archivedate=1 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a May 2014 column, the prominent EFF member Jackie Shandu declared his party a \"proudly [[Sankarism|Sankarist]] formation\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Shandu|first=Jackie|date=22 May 2014|title=The Sankarist makings of the EFF|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|newspaper=[[Daily Maverick]]|location=[[Johannesburg]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106000454/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|archivedate=6 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF has been vocal in its criticism of black business owners and black owners of mining companies in South Africa. In an address at the [[Oxford Union]] in November 2015, Malema spoke out against billionaire mining company owner Patrice Motsepe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|title=Business Day|website=www.bdlive.co.za|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229135821/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|archivedate=29 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|title=Patrice Motsepe has no power\u201a says Malema|last=Jordaan|first=Buchule Raba And Nomahlubi|website=Times LIVE|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127215142/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|archivedate=27 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Further protests in 2015, the EFF delivered demands that included the socialization of the mining sector and called for more explicit targets for the 26% BEE ownership required by law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|title=Yes and no to EFF\u2019s list of demands|last=John|first=Victoria|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050240/http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|archivedate=28 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The EFF is a vocal proponent of expanding the role of [[State-owned enterprises of South Africa|South African state owned enterprises]] in the country's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techfinancials.co.za/2019/02/03/eff-wants-state-to-create-ai-robotics-and-biotechnology-firms/|title=EFF Wants State To Create AI, Robotics And BioTechnology Firms|last=Lourie|first=Gugu|date=2019-02-03|website=TechFinancials|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/the-effs-2019-election-manifesto-iv|title=The EFF`s 2019 election manifesto (IV) - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>\n\nMalema addressed a crowd in Marikana, Rustenburg in the platinum mining area, blaming mining companies and calling out platinum mining company Lonmin in particular, for poverty in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|title=SABC News - Malema blames mining companies for high levels of poverty:Thursday 7 July 2016|last=Tatai|first=Sello|website=www.sabc.co.za|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127232029/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|archivedate=27 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe party supports the re-introduction of the [[Capital punishment in South Africa|death penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|title=iafrica.com Juju wants death penalty|website=News.iafrica.com|accessdate=2016-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901181605/http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|archivedate=1 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|title=Malema wants death penalty #EFFlaunch &#124; Economic Freedom Fighters - EFF|publisher=Economic Freedom Fighters|date=2013-10-13|accessdate=2016-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126014743/http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|archivedate=26 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, after [[2016 South African municipal elections|local elections]] in South Africa, the EFF has suggested that they will back the Democratic Alliance in hung-metro areas, but would not be entering into a coalition with any political party in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|title=Malema says the EFF won't form coalitions, but will support DA in hung metros|last=Feltham|first=Luke|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050103/http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|archivedate=28 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was the only parliamentary party that opposed the 2018 political party funding bill.<ref name=\"citizenFundingRejectionReasons\">https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1871025/reasons-why-the-eff-rejects-the-political-party-funding-bill/</ref>\n\n==High-profile members==\nHigh-profile members of the Central Command Team include [[Floyd Shivambu]], [[Fana Mokoena]] and [[Mbuyiseni Ndlozi]] (National Spokesperson).<ref name=\"EFF Central Command\">{{cite web|author=Economic Freedom Fighters|title=Central Command Team|url=http://www.effonline.org/structure|publisher=effonline.org|accessdate=21 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812200344/http://effighters.org.za/structure/officials/|archivedate=12 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Controversial businessman [[Kenny Kunene]] joined the Central Command Team in July 2013 before resigning from the Central Command Team on 20 August 2013 and from the organisation on 26 August 2013.<ref name=\"Sushi\">{{cite news|title='Sushi King' quits EFF leadership|author=Poloko Tau|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|newspaper=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|date=21 August 2013|accessdate=24 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824143456/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|archivedate=24 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ExitKunene\">{{cite news|title=Kunene quits EFF|author=[[South African Press Association|SAPA]]|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|newspaper=[[News24]]|date=26 August 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829084845/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|archivedate=29 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 4 November 2013, it was announced that [[Dali Mpofu]] had left the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) after 33 years of membership and joined the EFF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|title=Dali Mpofu joins EFF - Cape Times|publisher=IOL.co.za|date=2013-11-04|accessdate=2013-11-23|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202233822/http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|archivedate=2 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Musician and actress [[Ntando Duma]] also publicly pledged allegiance to EFF in February 2019.\n\n==Support base==\nAccording to a November 2013 [[Ipsos]] survey, the party's supporters are younger than average, with 49% being younger than 24, overwhelmingly black (99%) and mostly male, with women representing only 33% of the support base. A disproportionate number of supporters live in Malema's home province of [[Limpopo]] (28%), while only 1% live in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], a more populous province.<ref name=ipsos>{{cite web|title=The supporter profiles of SA`s three largest parties|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|publisher=Politicsweb|accessdate=6 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222022154/http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A 2018 survey conducted by social research company Citizen Surveys found that around 70% of EFF supporters were between the ages of 18 - 34, overwhelmingly black (97%), mostly based in major metropolitan cities (48%), predominantly male (62%) with 43% of their support base located in [[Gauteng|Gauteng Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizensurveys.net/citizen-surveys-how-many-white-eff-supporters-exist-and-11-other-stats/|title=Citizen Surveys: How many white EFF supporters exist, and 11 other stats|last=|first=|date=1 November 2018|website=Citizen Surveys|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nThe party was expected to make an impact in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], taking between 4 per cent and 8 per cent of the national vote. This was potentially enough for the party to hold [[Balance of power (parliament)|the balance of power]] in provinces where the governing African National Congress was in danger of losing its absolute majority.<ref name=\"irishtimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|title=Economic Freedom Fighters on rise in South Africa|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=6 May 2014|newspaper=The Irish Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506162746/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|archivedate=6 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The ANC retained is absolute majority whilst the EFF got 6.35% of the vote in the 2014 election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|title=ANC wins 249 seats|last=|first=|date=2014-05-12|website=News24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512215131/http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|archive-date=12 May 2014|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===National elections===\n====National Assembly====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total votes\n!Share of vote\n!Seats \n!+/\u2013\n!Government\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]<ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\">{{Cite web|title=2014 National and Provincial Elections Results - 2014 National and Provincial Election Results|url=http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|publisher=IEC|accessdate=11 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510231542/http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|archivedate=10 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|1,169,259\n|6.35%\n|{{Composition bar|25|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 25\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|1,881,521\n|10.79%\n|{{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 19\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|}\n\n====National Council of Provinces====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total # of<br/>seats won\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|{{Composition bar|7|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 7\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|{{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|}\n\n===Municipal elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n![[2016 South African municipal elections|2016]]<ref name=\"iec_summary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|title=Results Summary - All Ballots|publisher=elections.org.za|accessdate=11 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808191111/http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|archivedate=8 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|3,202,679\n|8.31%\n|-\n|}\n\n===Provincial elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n!rowspan=2|Election<br><ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\"/><ref name=\"dash\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.org.za/NPEDashboard/app/dashboard.html|title=Results Dashboard|website=www.elections.org.za|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n!colspan=2|[[Eastern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Free State (province)|Free State]]\n!colspan=2|[[Gauteng]]\n!colspan=2|[[KwaZulu-Natal|Kwazulu-Natal]]\n!colspan=2|[[Limpopo]]\n!colspan=2|[[Mpumalanga]]\n!colspan=2|[[North West (South African province)|North-West]]\n!colspan=2|[[Northern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Western Cape]]\n|- \n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|3.48%||2/63\n|8.15%||2/30\n|10.30%||8/73\n|1.85%||2/80\n|10.74%||6/49\n|6.26%||2/30\n|13.21%||5/33\n|4.96%||2/30\n|2.11%||1/42\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|7.84%||5/63\n|12.58%||4/30\n|14.69%||11/73\n|9.71%||8/80\n|14.43%||7/49\n|12.79%||4/30\n|18.36%||6/33\n|9.71%||3/30\n|4.04%||2/42\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\nOn 6 August 2015 the EFF announced that it has secured a Constitutional court case for its [[Jacob Zuma]] campaign of \"#PayBackTheMoney\". The case was heard on the 9 February 2016. The Judgement was released by Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng. The judgement stated that The President has violated the Constitution of South Africa, along with the [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker of the National Assembly]] [[Baleka Mbete]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} The President was given 60 days to fulfill the requirements of the Public Protector [[Thuli Madonsela]].<ref name=\"ZumaConCourt\">{{cite news|title=Lets meet in court, Malema tells Zuma|author=Emsie Ferreira|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=26 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201155340/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|archivedate=1 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2018 the EFF tabled a motion in The National Assembly to amend the Constitution so as to allow for the expropriation of land without compensation. The motion, brought by the EFF leader [[Julius Malema]], was adopted with a vote of 241 in support, and 83 against. The only parties who did not support the motion were the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], [[Freedom Front Plus]], [[Cope]] and the [[African Christian Democratic Party|ACDP]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Land Expropriation is one of the EFF's Seven cardinal pillars.<ref name=\"LandExpropriation\">{{cite news|title=National Assembly adopts motion on land expropriation without compensation|author=Jan Gerber|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|date=27 February 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920012156/https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|archivedate=2018-09-20|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the student wing of the EFF, the EFF Student Command won many universities across the country. The red berets defeated the ANC-aligned [[South African Students Congress]] (Sasco) at the [[Durban University of Technology]], the [[University of Zululand]] and [[Mangosuthu University of Technology]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} They also won in Cape Town, the District Six, Mowbray and Bellville [[Cape Peninsula University of Technology]] (CPUT) campuses with landslide victories, meaning they now are in charge of the institution's SRC. They also won the [[University of Cape Town]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Peter Keetse, president of the EFFSC, said the win was a warning shot for what was going to happen in 2019 national general elections. He said the youth were the influencers of the future, \u201ctherefore, this is an indication of what is to follow\u201d.<ref name=\"EFFStudentCommand\">{{cite news|title=Comrades see red as students back EFF on campus|author=Kwandokuhle Njoli|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sunday-tribune/news/comrades-see-red-as-students-back-eff-on-campus-17275465|date=30 September 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms and controversies==\nThe ANC has accused the Zimbabwean ruling party, the [[ZANU\u2013PF|Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] (ZANU\u2013PF), of supporting the EFF in order to destabilise the ANC.<ref name=\"bdliveMantashe\">{{cite news|title=Mantashe hits out at EFF for 'distorting the Freedom Charter'|author=Natasha Marrian|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|newspaper=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801072713/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|archivedate=1 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, a group of 17 former EFF members and councillors in the [[Northern Cape]] accused the party's senior leadership of corruption and sexual exploitation of more junior female party members.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2019199/expelled-eff-members-accuse-malema-shivambu-of-corruption-want-to-work-with-hawks/|title=Expelled EFF members accuse Malema, Shivambu of corruption, want to work with Hawks|last=reporter|first=Citizen|date=7 October 2018|work=The Citizen|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en}}</ref>  Four months later two former female employees of the EFF claimed that party leadership intimidated and engaged in acts of bullying behaviour towards them and other party staff members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/more-women-make-claims-of-eff-bullying-and-abuse-20190216|title=More women make claims of EFF bullying and abuse|last=Peter|first=Zamayirha|date=2019-02-16|website=CityPress|language=en|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 a former member of the EFF's central command, Thembinkosi Rawula, accused senior party leaders of dictatorial leadership practices and of using party finances for personal benefit.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/disgruntled-eff-member-slams-malema-shivambu-for-taking-vbs-donation-party-denies-claims-20190405|title=Former EFF leader accuses Malema, Shivambu of taking VBS donation, party denies claims|last=Lizeka Tandwa and Tshidi Madia|date=2019-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> The EFF denied Rawula's accusation and stated that they would sue him for defamation as well as make the party's financials public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-to-sue-rawula-offers-journalists-access-to-effs-financial-records-20190410|title=Malema to sue Rawula, offers journalists access to EFF's financial records|last=Tandwa|first=Lizeka|date=2019-04-10|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was found guilty of [[Defamation|defamation of character]] in May 2019 by the South Gauteng High Court and ordered to pay R500,000 in damages to former Finance Minister [[Trevor Manuel]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-court-finds-effs-comments-about-trevor-manuel-defamatory-and-false/|title=Court vindicates Trevor Manuel in defamation battle with EFF|last=Quintal|first=Genevieve|date=30 May 2019|website=BusinessLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> Manuel brought the EFF and its leader, Julius Malema, to court after they alleged that the appointment of [[Edward Kieswetter]] as commissioner of SARS by Manuel was the result of nepotism.<ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/14/challenge-me-don-t-defame-manuel-to-eff-in-kieswetter-matter|title=Challenge me, don't defame - Manuel to EFF in Kieswetter nepotism matter|last=Modise|first=Kgomotso|website=ewn.co.za|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>  Following the judgement Manuel stated that he would be donating the R500,000 in damages to victims of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters#VBS Mutual Bank|VBS Mutual Bank scandal]] which the EFF is alleged to have participated in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fin24.com/Economy/trevor-manuel-i-dont-need-a-cent-of-eff-money-20190531-2|title=Trevor Manuel: I don't need a cent of EFF money|last=Khumalo|first=Sibongile|date=2019-05-31|website=Fin24|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>  \n\nFollowing a string of court case losses for inciting supporters to commit acts of either intimidation (against Karima Brown), land invasion ([[AfriForum]]) or of defamation of character (against Trevor Manuel) the party was left with combined court costs amounting to almost R1 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/courts/2144536/eff-wallows-in-legal-debt-of-almost-r1m/|title=EFF wallows in legal debt of almost R1m|last=Watson|first=Amanda|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>  \n\n===Alleged Corruption===\n\n==== Tenders ====\nA number of articles published by investigative journalists have accused the party of using their influence to earn improper payments from government suppliers in cities where the EFF has significant representative power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in \u2018kickbacks\u2019 in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>  An investigation by the [[amaBhungane]] centre for investigative journalism stated that the EFF received R500,000 in kickbacks from a company in return for a R1.26 billion contract to manage a fleet of vehicles used by the [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality|City of Johannesburg]] with tacit acquiescence of the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/firm-that-won-r1bn-joburg-fleet-contract-paid-malema-eff-slush-fund/|title=Firm that won R1bn Jo'burg fleet contract paid Malema-EFF 'slush-fund' - amaBhungane|last=Micah Reddy and Stefaans Br\u00fcmmer|date=29 November 2018|website=amabhungane.org|language=en-ZA|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/tender-comrades-part-1-trailing-the-juju-tractor/|title=Tender comrades part 1: Trailing the Juju tractor|website=amaBhungane|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Another investigation alleges that the party improperly benefited from the awarding of a fuel supply contract for the [[City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality|City of Tshwane]] netting the party R15 million from successful contractors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-29-tender-comrades-part-two-tshwane-tenderpreneurs-r15m-eff-tithe/|title=AMABHUNGANE: Tender Comrades Part Two: Tshwane tenderpreneur\u2019s R15m \u2018EFF tithe\u2019|last=amaBhungane|first=Stefaans Brummer & Micah Reddy for|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n====VBS Mutual Bank====\n{{See also|VBS Mutual Bank}}\nFollowing the publication of a [[South African Reserve Bank]] report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resbank.co.za/Lists/News%20and%20Publications/Attachments/8830/VBS%20Mutual%20Bank%20-%20The%20Great%20Bank%20Heist.pdf|title=The Great Bank Heist: Investigator's Report to the Prudential Authority|last=Motau|first=Terry|date=10 October 2018|website=South African Reserve Bank|page=135|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> into the collapse of [[VBS Mutual Bank]] implicating EFF deputy president Floyd Shivambu's brother media reports came out alleging that Shivambu received R10 million in illicit payments from VBS prior to it being placed under [[Receivership|curatorship]] in March 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-10-11-the-shivambu-brothers-and-the-great-vbs-heist/|title=The Shivambu Brothers and the Great VBS Heist|last=Van Wyk|first=Pauli|date=11 October 2018|work=[[Daily Maverick]]|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-10-12-00-pic-vbs-floyd-and-his-baby-brother|title=PIC, VBS, Floyd and his baby brother|last=Jika|first=Sabelo Skiti, Thanduxolo|date=12 October 2018|work=The M&G Online|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref> Prior to the publication of the Reserve Bank's report the EFF criticised the Reserve Bank for placing VBS under curatorship and accused it of victimising VBS on racial grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/single-post/2018/03/11/EFF-STATEMENT-ON-VBS-CURATORSHIP|title=EFF STATEMENT ON VBS CURATORSHIP {{!}} EFF: Economic Freedom Fighters|last=Ndlozi|first=Mbuyiseni Quintin|date=11 March 2018|website=Economic Freedom Fighters|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref> The EFF stated that it had seen no evidence that Shivambu received the R10 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-there-are-exchanges-of-money-between-floyd-and-brian-shivambu-but-floyd-did-not-get-money-from-vbs-says-eff/|title=Money was exchanged - but Floyd did not get any from VBS bank, says Malema|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> and called for government to recapitalise VBS Mutual Bank<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-calls-for-vbs-to-be-recapitalised-17501083|title=EFF calls for VBS to be recapitalised {{!}} IOL News|last=Zintle|first=Mahlati|date=16 October 2018|work=IOL|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> whilst also taking legal action against those mentioned in the Reserve Bank report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-malema-vbs-allegations-meant-to-discredit-the-eff/|title=Malema: VBS allegations meant to 'discredit the EFF'|last=Mvumvu|first=Zingisa|date=16 October 2018|work=Dispatch Live|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> A follow up investigation by the ''[[Daily Maverick]]'' alleged that the EFF illicitly received R1.8 million of VBS money through a network of proxy companies with the party's leadership (notably Shivambu and Malema) also illicitly receiving money though this network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-21-vbs-bank-heist-effs-family-ties-and-moneyed-connections/|title=VBS bank heist: EFF's family ties and moneyed connections|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=21 November 2018|work=Daily Maverick|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> After being approached by the ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'' for comment on his personal financial expenses Floyd Shivambu admitted that money from VBS, channeled through his brother, was used to buy his [[Range Rover Sport]] valued at R680,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-09-26-vbss-r680k-paid-for-floyds-wheels/|title=VBS\u2019s R680k paid for Floyd\u2019s wheels|last=Skiti|first=Thanduxolo Jika, Sabelo|website=The M&G Online|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nA follow up investigation by the ''Daily Maverick'' found that R454,000 of VBS money was used to pay for the 2017 EFF birthday celebration.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-27-cruising-nicely-on-vbs-effs-parties-lies-and-looted-money/|title=SCORPIO: 'Cruising nicely' on VBS: EFF's Parties, Lies and Looted Money|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> It also found that a total of R16.1 million was channeled through a Shivambu associated company largely for the benefit of the EFF.<ref name=\":5\" /> An additional investigation traced financial statements from an account that received VBS funds and allegedly controlled by Julius Malema; leading the author of the investigation to estimate that Malema received and directly benefited from R5.3-million illegally taken from VBS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-08-vbs-theft-money-laundering-lifes-little-luxuries-julius-malemas-time-of-spending-dangerously/|title=SCORPIO: VBS Theft, Money Laundering & Life's Little Luxuries: Julius Malema's time of spending dangerously|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=8 September 2019|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> Additional media reports in October 2019 alleged that the party received R4 million of VBS funds into a slush fund that was channeled to Malema via a company named Santaclara Trading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2190574/over-r4m-in-concerning-payments-made-into-malema-slush-fund-report/|title=Over R4m in 'concerning' payments made into Malema slush fund \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-10-13-julius-malemas-slush-fund-exposed/|title=Julius Malema's 'slush fund' exposed|website=TimesLIVE|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-linked-to-another-company-that-had-a-vbs-loan-report-20191013|title=Malema linked to another company that had a VBS loan - report|date=2019-10-13|website=News24|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nA former member of the EFF's leadership accused the party leadership of accepting donations from VBS Mutual Bank prior to its collapse.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMalema later forwarded a [[conspiracy theory]] that the VBS collapse was part of a plot intended to damage the EFF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-vbs-was-meant-to-collapse-and-finish-eff-malema-20190503|title=WATCH: 'VBS was meant to collapse and finish EFF' \u2013 Malema|date=2019-05-03|website=News24|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===Ideology===\nFeminists and the [[National Union of Metalworkers of South Africa]] have criticised the party's militarism and \"military command structure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179#.Usa_NvQW3Y5|title=Numsa wary of \u2018capitalist\u2019 Malema|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103182553/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179|archive-date=3 January 2014|author=Shanti Aboobaker|work=Sunday Independent|date=29 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen/|title=EFF & the Return of the Warrior Citizen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410024005/http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen|archive-date=10 April 2014|author=Siphokazi Magadla|work=Thought Leader|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2016 a group calling themselves \"Anonymous Africa\", claiming to be associated with the [[Hacktivism|hacktivist]] group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]], perpetrated a [[Denial-of-service attack|DDoS attack]] on the EFF's website stating the reason for the attack was the party's \"nationalist socialist rhetoric\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|title=EXCLUSIVE: Why Anonymous 'hacked' the SABC, Gupta websites|website=Fin24|access-date=2016-06-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617140057/http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|archivedate=17 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[South African Communist Party]] also condemns this party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacp.org.za/main.php?ID=5299|title=SACP supports ANC, condemns Julius Malema`s propagation of war in the strongest possible terms, calls on the police ?to act swiftly in terms of the rule of law|website=www.sacp.org.za|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n===Violence and bigotry===\nVusi Khoza, the party's candidate for [[Premier of KwaZulu-Natal]], has a criminal conviction for his involvement in what was believed to be a [[Xenophobia in South Africa|xenophobic attack]] on foreigners at Albert Park, [[Durban]] in December 2009.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164#.Uy0Y3vmSzY4 EFF\u2019s KZN man has criminal past] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091149/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164 |date=22 March 2014 }}, BHEKI MBANJWA, ''The Daily News'', 2014</ref>\n\nFeminists have characterised leading members of the party as [[Misogyny|misogynist]].<ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me/ Floyd Shivambu: Despicable Me] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224084746/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me |date=24 December 2013 }}, Sipho Hlongwane, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ Remembering Thomas Sankara, the EFF\u2019s muse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224094726/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ |date=24 December 2013 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/ Elections Analysis: The Economic Freedom Fighters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322090232/http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/|date=22 March 2014}}, Sonja Bornman, ''Feminist SA'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape EFF: Two senior party officials accused of involvement in 2008 gang rape] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091542/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape |date=22 March 2014 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2014, eight members of the EFF were forcibly removed from the legislature after their attire of red overalls carrying the slogan \"asijiki\" (meaning \"we are not turning back\") was found to be inappropriate by presiding officer, Ntombi Mekgwe.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.enca.com/eff-kicked-out-gauteng-legislature |title=EFF kicked out of Gauteng Legislature |publisher=enca.co.za |date=2014-07-01 |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref> Hundreds of EFF members protested against the ruling on 22 July near the legislature building.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ewn.co.za/2014/07/22/EFF-storm-Gauteng-Provincial-Legislature |title=EFF storm Gauteng Provincial Legislature |publisher=ewn.co.za |date=2014-07-24 |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref>\n\nIn February, 2016, during [[FeesMustFall|violent university protests]] characterised by arson and vandalism, EFF Youth leader Omphile Seleke posted instructions for making petrol bombs on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|title=EFF\u2019s \u2018petrol bomb recipe\u2019 fuels Tuks fears|last=de Lange|first=Ilse|date=2016-02-29|work=The Citizen|access-date=2017-04-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414081535/http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|archivedate=14 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, EFF Deputy President [[Floyd Shivambu]] congratulated the party supporters for causing damage to various [[H&M]] stores<ref>{{cite tweet|number=952114009448304640|user=FloydShivambu|title=That @hm nonsense of a clothing store is now facing consequences for its racism.|date=13 Jan 2018}}</ref> across South Africa due to a picture of a young black child wearing a green hoodie reading, \"Coolest Monkey in the Jungle\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|title=H&M monkey hoodie sparks outrage for \"racist\" image - CBS News|date=2018-01-08|work=[[CBS News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108222136/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|title=H&M apologizes for using black child to sell 'coolest monkey' top|date=2018-01-08|work=[[CNN]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108143043/http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|title=H&M slammed as racist for 'monkey in the jungle' hoodie|date=2018-01-08|work=[[CNBC]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108165628/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|title=H&M is apologizing for a product image called out as racist - Quartz|date=2018-01-08|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108235715/https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|title=H&M apologises following backlash over 'racist' image of child model on website - The Independent|date=2018-01-08|work=[[The Independent]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108173805/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|title=H&M Faces Twitter Backlash for \"Racist\" Hoodie - Pret-a-Reporter|date=2018-01-08|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108095220/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[Vodacom]] store in [[Polokwane]] was damaged and looted by EFF members following a presentation by [[Corruption Watch (South Africa)|Corruption Watch]] at the 2018 Vodacom Awards which included an image depicting EFF leaders Malema and Shivambu as \"abusers of Democracy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/matter-now-closed-eff-vodacom-issue-joint-statement-following-unrest-20181204|title='Matter now closed' - EFF, Vodacom issue joint statement following unrest|last=Seleka|first=Ntwaagae|date=2018-12-04|website=News24|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mybroadband.co.za/news/business-telecoms/288272-why-vodacom-met-with-the-eff.html|title=Why Vodacom met with the EFF|last=Staff Writer|date=4 December 2018|website=mybroadband.co.za|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, after the SONA address in parliament by the SA President, EFF MP [[Marshall Dlamini]] physically assaulted a member of the presidential security team after a disagreement between EFF MPs and the security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-eff-mp-slaps-man-after-sona-20190208|title=EFF MP slaps man after SONA|last=Gerber|first=Jan|date=8 February 2019|website=www.news24.com|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n====Actions against journalists and the media====\nJournalist Ranjeni Munusamy lodged an affidavit in December 2018 detailing threatening remarks, intimidation, harassment and personal attacks made by party members, including Malema, towards her and other journalists<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanef.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Part-2.pdf|title=Supporting Affidavit: Navaranjeni Munusamy|last=Munusamy|first=Ranjeni|date=19 December 2018|website=South African National Editors Forum|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> targeted by the party. The affidavit was supported by the South African National Editors Forum and other notable South African journalists such as [[Max du Preez]], Pauli VanWyk, Adriaan Jurgens Basson, and Barry Bateman.<ref name=\":1\" /> The EFF denied any involvement in attacks on Munusamy and other journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-12-19-eff-denies-involvement-in-attacks-on-journalists/|title=EFF denies involvement in attacks on journalists|last=Shange|first=Naledi|date=19 December 2018|website=www.timeslive.co.za|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>{{quote box|quote=''\"We need to ask the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|IEC]] how such a party can be on the ballot box. It threatens journalists. It encourages its supporters to make rape threats and sexual assault threats. It wants to dictate what I can do as a journalist.\"''<br/>\u2014Karima Brown<ref name=\"KB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack|publisher=African News Agency|date=20 March 2016|accessdate=6 March 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306215040/https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|archivedate=6 March 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right}}\nSouth African political journalist Karima Brown was the target of verbal abuse and threats of violence by EFF supporters following the EFF's publication of her personal contact details. This led charges with the police and Equity Court being laid against the party amidst speculation that this instance might be in breach of South Africa's Electoral Code of Conduct. Parties in breach of the code risk having their registration to run in elections being revoked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack {{!}} IOL News|website=www.iol.co.za|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> Malema stated on the incident that journalists have no privileges whilst accusing Brown of being a state agent and denied that EFF supporters were making threatening remarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/how-do-you-hold-an-underground-editor-accountable-malema-on-karima-brown-matter-20190306|title='How do you hold an underground editor accountable ' \u2013 Malema on Karima Brown matter|date=2019-03-06|website=News24|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> The court found in favour of Brown and ruled that the EFF had contravened the South African electoral code by inciting its supports to harass Brown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-06-06-eff-court-losses-mount-as-karima-brown-wins-battle-but-faces-criticism-of-her-own/|title=REPORT: EFF court losses mount as Karima Brown wins battle, but faces criticism of her own|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the publication of an article by the amaBhungane Centre for investigative journalism looking into allegations of corruption by the EFF the party controversially announced that it would be banning both amaBhungane and the ''Daily Maverick'' from its public events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in 'kickbacks' in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-13-this-is-what-panic-looks-like/|title=Editorial: This is What Panic Looks Like|last=Maverick|first=Daily|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sanef-appalled-by-malemas-call-to-ban-amabhungane-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190913|title=Sanef 'appalled' by Malema's call to ban amaBhungane, Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events|date=2019-09-13|website=News24|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> and announced that they would be treated an enemies of the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-shall-treat-them-as-enemies-malema-bans-amabhungane-and-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190912|title=Malema bans amaBhungane and Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events: 'We shall treat them as enemies'|date=2019-09-12|website=News24|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 the EFF was forced to publicly apologies and pay damages following a Gauteng High Court judgment that the party had made and spread false allegations that two journalists, Thandeka Gqubule and Anton Harber, were apartheid era 'StratCom' agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-retracts-stratcom-agent-allegations-against-gqubule-and-harber-apologises-after-court-order-20200125|title=EFF retracts 'Stratcom agent' allegations against Gqubule and Harber, apologises after court order|date=2020-01-25|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-24-eff-ndlozi-have-twenty-four-hours-to-pay-damages-to-journalists/|title=NEWSFLASH: EFF, Ndlozi have twenty-four hours to pay damages to journalists|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n===Racial and ethnic prejudice===\nSince its establishment the EFF has made a number of controversial racially or ethnically based statements about a number of South African minority groups. The EFF is widely criticised for inciting and perpetuating racism.<ref>[http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899 The EFF and the Question of National Unity] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413154904/http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899|date=13 April 2014}}, Duncan, Jane, ''SACSIS WEBSITE'', 29 JAN, 2014</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|title=\u2018EFF must #PayBackTheMoney for damage to varsities\u2019|last=Sain|first=Raahil|date=2016-03-08|access-date=2017-04-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414162203/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \n\n====Anti-Indian prejudice====\nThe South African Minority Rights Equality Movement initiated a court case against Malema for inciting racial sentiment by stating that a \"majority of [[Indian South Africans|Indians]] are racist\" at an EFF Youth Day rally in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/group-to-take-juliusmalema-to-court-for-racist-rant-15526571|title=Group to take #JuliusMalema to court for racist rant {{!}} IOL News|last=Mngoma|first=Nosipho|date=18 June 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|publisher=The Mercury|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was criticised by the [[South African Council of Churches]], the [[Ahmed Kathrada Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/no-one-is-going-to-intimidate-us-eff-hits-back-at-clergy-and-ahmed-kathrada-foundation-20181122|title='No one is going to intimidate us' - EFF hits back at clergy and Ahmed Kathrada Foundation|work=News24|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> and the ANC<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-bullies-trying-to-hide-their-own-shenanigans-anc-chief-whip-mthembu-20181123|title='EFF bullies' trying to 'hide their own shenanigans' - ANC chief whip Mthembu|work=News24|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> for comparing Public Enterprises Minister [[Pravin Gordhan]] to a \"dog\" whilst protesting the [[The Judicial Commission of Inquiry into Allegations of State Capture|Zondo Commission]] inquiry into government corruption. The EFF also accused the anti-corruption investigators of being members of an \"[[Indian South Africans|Indian]] [[cabal]]\" commenting on the presence of Indian South African's making up the investigative team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://city-press.news24.com/Voices/indian-cabal-narrative-is-to-protect-the-looting-project-20181119|title=\u2018Indian cabal\u2019 narrative is to protect the looting project|work=CityPress|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-to-gordhan-i-am-not-scared-of-the-indian-cabal|title=Malema to Gordhan: I am not scared of the Indian cabal|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> The EFF also accused Gordhan and his daughter of corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-11-23-00-gordhan-decries-eff-attack-on-daughter/|title=Gordhan decries EFF attack on daughter|last=Smit|first=Sarah|website=The M&G Online|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> The EFF accusations were proven false<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Analysis/fact-checked-julius-malemas-charges-against-pravin-gordhan-20181128|title=FACT CHECKED: EFF's charges against Pravin Gordhan|last=Jean le Roux, Kyle Cowan, Pieter du Toit and Adriaan Basson|date=2018-11-28|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-29-snowbank-bleff-pravin-gordhan-and-the-imaginary-r675m-canadian-account/|title=SnowBank \u2013 BLEFF, Pravin Gordhan and the imaginary R6...|last=Poplak|first=Richard|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> and Gordhan laid charge of defamation against Malema stating that the EFF's \"determined defence of corruption and the corrupt, using personal attacks, racism and alleged hate speech is not acceptable and must be challenged.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/pravin-gordhan-lays-defamation-charges-against-malema-18267798|title=Pravin Gordhan lays defamation charges against Malema {{!}} IOL News|last=Ndaba|first=Baldwin|date=26 November 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>  The Equality Court found that the EFF was not guilty of hate speech in its statements relating to Gordhan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/pravin-gordhan-vs-julius-malema-the-high-court-jud|title=Pravin Gordhan vs Julius Malema|last=Sutherland|first=Roland|date=31 October 2019|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-10-31-judge-slates-malemas-juvenile-rant-as-eff-leader-wins-case-against-gordhan/|title=Judge slates Malema's 'juvenile' rant as EFF leader wins case against Gordhan|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> EFF leadership and its supporters have been criticised for using Gordhan's second name, Jamnadas, as a racial [[Dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]] to highlight to his Indian ethnicity in a [[pejorative]] way and question his status as a South African on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-23-pravin-jamnadas-gordhan-a-case-study-when-your-name-is-weaponised-by-haters-on-twitter/|title=POPULIST DOG WHISTLES: Pravin Jamnadas Gordhan, a case study: When your name is weaponised on Twitter|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\nANC member and government minister [[Jackson Mthembu]] accused the EFF of being racist and having a \"deep-seated hatred\" for Indian South Africans whilst criticizing the party's pursuit of Gordhan whilst participating in a parliamentary debate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-07-17-of-course-you-are-racist-you-are-jackson-mthembu-tells-eff-mps/|title='Of course, you are racist. You are,' Jackson Mthembu tells EFF MPs|last=Makinana|first=Andisiwe|date=17 July 2019|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/cigarettes-corruption-and-racism-why-the-eff-hates-gordhan-according-to-jackson-mthembu-20190718|title=Cigarettes, corruption and racism: Why the EFF hates Gordhan, according to Jackson Mthembu|last=van Diemen|first=Ethan|date=2019-07-18|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n====Anti-white prejudice====\nMalema stated at a political rally in 2016 that \u201cWe are not calling for the slaughter of [[White South Africans|white people]]\u201a at least for now\". When asked for comment by a news agency, the ANC spokesperson, Zizi Kodwa stated that there will be no comment from the ANC, as \"[h]e [Malema] was addressing his own party supporters.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Malema slammed for comments on whites|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|accessdate=30 May 2017|publisher=ENCA|date=8 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417053045/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While still the ANCYL leader, Malema was taken to the [[Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimination Act, 2000|Equality Court]] by [[AfriForum]] for repeatedly singing \u201c[[Dubul' ibhunu|dubul\u2019 ibhunu]]\u201d, which translate as \u201cshoot the [[boer]] [white farmer]\u201d. The ANC supported Malema, though AfriForum and the ANC reached a settlement before the appeal case was due to be argued in the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\n\nSouth Africa's [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] disqualified EFF councillor Thabo Mabotja in the 2016 local elections due a [[Twitter|tweet]] made by Mabotja calling for violence against white South Africans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|title=IEC disqualifies EFF councillor for racist tweet|date=2016-08-29|work=eNCA|access-date=2017-04-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414082702/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/elections/news/eff-councillor-candidate-disqualified-after-calling-for-whites-to-be-hacked-and-killed-reports-20160729|title=EFF councillor candidate disqualified after calling for whites to be 'hacked and killed' reports|date=2016-07-29|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> The EFF welcomed the commission's decision and renounced Mabotja.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/hes-on-his-own-juju-says-of-mabotja|title='He's on his own' Juju says of Mabotja|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/electoral-court-right-to-give-thabo-mabotja-the-ch|title=Electoral Court right to give Thabo Mabotja the chop|last=|first=|date=|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n\nJulius Malema, leader of the Economic Freedom Fighters, stated at a political rally in 2018 that \"''Go After A White Man... We Are Cutting The Throat Of Whiteness\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-are-cutting-the-throat-of-whiteness-malema-on-plans-to-remove-trollip-20180304|title='We are cutting the throat of whiteness' \u2013 Malema on plans to remove Trollip|work=News24|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>'' This led to the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] accusing the EFF's leader, Malema, of [[racism]] and not sharing the more tolerant views of South Africans broadly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/south-africans-dont-share-malemas-racist-views-maimane-13714966|title=South Africans don't share Malema's racist views - Maimane {{!}} IOL News|access-date=2018-03-11}}</ref> The EFF later stated that the reference to the \"throat of whiteness\" was a metaphorical reference to destroying [[white privilege]] and was not referring or advocating harm to white people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2019-03-28-empty-analysis-will-not-deter-the-eff-from-its-core-task-reaching-out-to-the-electorate/|title=OPINIONISTA: Empty analysis will not deter the EFF from its core task \u2014 reaching out to the electorate|last=Thambo|first=Sinawo|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of former Zimbabwean President [[Robert Mugabe]] EFF leader Julius Malema tweeted a number of controversial quotes from the late Mugabe that were interpreted as racially prejudiced towards white people.  Most notable was the quote that \"''The only white man you can trust is a dead white man''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-09-17-yep-its-hate-speech-says-sahrc-on-julius-malemas-dead-white-man-tweet/|title=Yep, it's hate speech, says SAHRC on Julius Malema's 'dead white man' tweet|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-15-malemas-mugabe-closing-gambit/|title=ANALYSIS: Malema\u2019s Mugabe closing gambit|last=Grootes|first=Stephen|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>  The [[South African Human Rights Commission]] (SAHRC) condemned the quote and stated that they would be taking Malema to court for allegedly spreading [[hate speech]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahrc.org.za/index.php/sahrc-media/news-2/item/2137-sahrc-to-take-malema-to-court-for-hate-speech|title=SAHRC to take Malema to court for hate speech|last=|first=|date=19 September 2019|website=South African Human Rights Commission|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Namibian Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n*[[Socialist Party of Azania]]\n*[[Workers and Socialist Party]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|last1=Van Onselen|first1=Gareth|title=Malema steals young communists' thunder|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q7p7lAID?url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|archivedate=6 June 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Pillay|first1=Verashni|title=EFF: You want land, a loan? You got it|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Mail & Guardian|date=21 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328111438/http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|archivedate=28 March 2014|url-status=live}}\n*Julius Malema (preface), [https://archive.org/details/EconomicFreedomFighters2014ElectionsManifesto ''EFF 2014 Elections Manifesto,''] Economic Freedom Fighters.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.effonline.org Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140918100051/http://effighters.org.za/ Old official website]\n*[http://economicfreedomfighters.org/ Supporter website]\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{South Africa political parties}}\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters| ]]\n[[Category:African and Black nationalist organizations in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalist political parties]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics]]\n[[Category:Political parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2013]]\n[[Category:National liberation movements in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-white racism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-Indian sentiment in Africa]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Left-wing populist parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use South African English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox political party\n|name=Economic Freedom Fighters\n|logo=File:Logo of the EFF.png\n|colorcode={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}\n|abbreviation=EFF\n|president = [[Julius Malema]]\n|chairperson = [[Veronica Mente]]\n|secretary_general = [[Marshall Dlamini]]\n|spokesperson = [[Vuyani Pambo]]\n|leader1_title = Deputy President\n|leader1_name = [[Floyd Shivambu]]\n|leader2_title = Deputy Secretary-General\n|leader2_name = [[Poppy Mailola]]\n|leader3_title = Treasurer-General\n|leader3_name = [[Omphile Moatwe]]\n|founder=Julius Malema\n|founded={{Start date|2013|07|26|df=yes}}\n|dissolved=<!--{{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n|split=[[African National Congress]]\n|headquarters=82 De Korte Street,<br>[[Johannesburg]],<br>[[Gauteng]]\n|newspaper=\n|student_wing=[[EFF Students Command]] (EFFSC)\n|youth_wing=\n|ideology={{Nowrap|[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/economicfreedomstruggle|title=EFF|accessdate=2016-02-24|via=Facebook|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105041413/https://www.facebook.com/economicfreedomstruggle|archivedate=5 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>https://www.effonline.org/constitution</ref><br>[[Anti-capitalism]]<ref name=\"aji\">{{cite web|url=http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201310142026-0023110|title=Economic Freedom Fighters Party reignites debate (in English)|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102192705/http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201310142026-0023110|archivedate=2 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"n24i\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Hundreds-gather-for-EFF-launch-20131013|title=Hundreds gather for EFF launch (in English)|publisher=[[News24]]|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104124450/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Hundreds-gather-for-EFF-launch-20131013|archivedate=4 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br>[[Anti-imperialism]]<br>[[Pan-Africanism]]<br>[[Anti-Europeanism]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=John|year=2016|title=Morning in South Africa|publisher=Indiana University Press|page=187}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Megan|year=2016|title=Performing Whitely in the Postcolony: Afrikaners in South African Theatrical and Public Life|publisher=University of Iowa Press|page=62}}</ref><br>[[Left-wing populism]]<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Times of India]]|title=ANC holds onto power in South Africa as other parties increase vote share|date=11 May 2018|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/anc-holds-onto-power-in-south-africa-as-other-parties-increase-vote-share/articleshow/69278436.cms}}</ref>}}\n|position={{nowrap|[[Far-left politics|Far-left]]<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-safrica-politics-malema/south-africas-malema-says-more-than-60-anc-mps-will-turn-on-zuma-idUSKBN1A61AP South Africa's Malema says more than 60 ANC MPs will turn on Zuma]. ''Reuters''. Authors - Ed Stoddard and Sisipho Skweyiya. Published 21 July 2017. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eti_DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&dq=Far-left+Economic+Freedom+Fighters&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4ooLL96raAhWJalAKHTa0AMAQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Social Changes in a Global World'']. p.66. Author - Ulrike Schuerkens. Published by SAGE. Published in London in 2017. Accessed via Google Books.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9MZODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA535&lpg=PA535&dq=Far-left+Economic+Freedom+Fighters&source=bl&ots=HZyA_KTESl&sig=agvCpZ2_jS7zZKdYQolUvHnm0Xs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEl5ew96raAhVSPsAKHSM8C7A4PBDoAQhgMAk#v=onepage&q=Far-left%20Economic%20Freedom%20Fighters&f=false ''The World Since 1945: An International History'']. p.535. 2nd edition. Authors - P. M. H. Bell and Mark Gilbert. Published by Bloomsbury in London. First published in 2001, 2nd edition in 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/chaos-in-parliament-as-party-gets-ejected-for-grilling-zuma-over-corruption-in-south-africa-10043286.html Chaos in parliament as party gets ejected for grilling Zuma over corruption in South Africa]. ''Independent''. Author - Lamiat Sabin. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201408222154-0024098 South African lawmakers disrupt parliament and demand Zuma #PayBackTheMoney]. ''AlJazeera''. Published 22 August 2014. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/world/266026/south-african-parliament-descends-into-chaos South African parliament descends into chaos]. ''Radio New Zealand''. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref>}}\n|international=\n|colours=[[Red]]<ref name=\"aji\"/><ref name=\"n24i\"/><ref name=\"dmi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|title=Red Tide: From 'economic freedom' to 'white genocide', extremism grabs the spotlight (in English)|publisher=[[Daily Maverick]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017020415/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|slogan=\"People\u2019s Power for Economic Freedom in Our Lifetime\"\n|seats1_title=[[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]]\n|seats1={{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats2_title=[[National Council of Provinces]]\n|seats2={{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats3_title={{nowrap|[[Pan-African Parliament]]}}\n|seats3={{Composition bar|1|5|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}<small>(South African seats)</small>\n|seats4_title=[[Provincial legislature (South Africa)|Provincial Legislatures]]\n|seats4={{Composition bar|50|430|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats5_title=[[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n|seats5={{Composition bar|30|270|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats6_title=[[Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n|seats6={{Composition bar|6|120|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|seats7_title=[[City of Cape Town]] (council)\n|seats7={{Composition bar|7|231|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|flag=\n|website={{Official URL}}\n|country=South Africa}}\nThe '''Economic Freedom Fighters''' ('''EFF''') is a [[South Africa]]n [[Far-left politics|far-left]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/southAfricaNews/idAFL5N1V80N0|title=South Africa's opposition EFF introduces bill to nationalise...|date=2018-08-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-23|language=en}}</ref> [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-Africanist]] [[political party]]. It was founded by expelled former [[African National Congress Youth League]] (ANCYL) President [[Julius Malema]], and his allies, in 2013.<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite news|title=Malema launches his Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Meggan Saville|url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|newspaper=Dispatch Online|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725200305/http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|archivedate=25 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Malema is President of the EFF, heading the Central Command Team which serves as the central structure of the party.<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite news|title=Malema takes command of Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Setumo Stone|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|newspaper=[[Business Day (South Africa)|Business Day]]|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130714113641/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|archivedate=14 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt is currently the third-largest party in both houses of the [[Parliament of South Africa|South African Parliament]].\n\n==History==\nAt a 26 July 2013 press briefing in [[Soweto]], Malema announced that the new party had over 1000 members, double the 500 required for registration with the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] (IEC).<ref name=\"EFF 1000\">{{cite news|title=EFF readies for election registration as over 1 000 members recruited|author=SAPA|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|newspaper=[[The Times (South Africa)|The Times]]|date=28 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730092849/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|archivedate=30 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The EFF is now registered with the IEC, after an objection to its registration by the [[Freedom Front Plus]] (FF+) was dismissed in September 2013.<ref name=\"It'sOfficial\">{{cite news|title=It's official: Malema's EFF is a political party|author=Verashni Pillay|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]|date=5 September 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907063401/http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|archivedate=7 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Splinters and infighting==\nIn 2015, the EFF suspended [[Member of parliament|MP]] Lucky Twala and expelled three MPs, Mpho Ramakatsa, Andile Mngxitama and [[Khanyisile Litchfield-Tshabalala]].<ref name=m.news24.com>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|title=Litchfield-Tshabalala UDM's new national organiser|author=Genevieve Quintal|date=2015-06-05|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930022925/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|archivedate=30 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mngxitama formed his own party, named [[Black First Land First]] (BLF), while Litchfield-Tshabalala joined the [[United Democratic Movement]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\nMalema has been chiefly accused by former members of purging his critics to consolidate his power, thus ruling the party with an iron fist. Malema acknowledged this criticism in a press conference and further went on to say, the party should have expelled more ill disciplined members.\n\n==Policies==\n[[File:EFF land march on Mandela Day 2014.JPG|thumb|A small march by the EFF on Mandela Day (18 July) 2014 near the parliament building in [[Cape Town]] protesting in support of [[land reform in South Africa]].]]\nThe EFF \"draws inspiration from the broad [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] tradition and [[Frantz Fanon|Fanonian]] schools of thought in their analyses of the state, imperialism, culture and class contradictions in every society\", according to one of its declarations.<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/declaration|title=Declaration|work=effonline.org}}</ref>\n\nIt criticises the [[African National Congress]] and their primary opposition, the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], for their allegedly pro-business stances, which it claims have sold out the black people of South Africa to capitalism as cheap labour. It promises to tackle corruption, provide quality social housing, and provide free primary healthcare and education for all, as well as proposing to [[expropriation|expropriate]] stolen land, nationalise the mining and banking sectors, double welfare grants and the minimum wage, and end the proposed toll system for highways.<ref name=\"irishtimes\"/>\n\nThe EFF takes significant inspiration from [[Thomas Sankara]] in terms of both style and ideology.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|last=Duval Smith|first=Alex|date=30 April 2014|title='Africa's Che Guevara': Thomas Sankara's legacy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|newspaper=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=[[London]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101053949/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|archivedate=1 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a May 2014 column, the prominent EFF member Jackie Shandu declared his party a \"proudly [[Sankarism|Sankarist]] formation\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Shandu|first=Jackie|date=22 May 2014|title=The Sankarist makings of the EFF|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|newspaper=[[Daily Maverick]]|location=[[Johannesburg]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106000454/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|archivedate=6 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF has been vocal in its criticism of black business owners and black owners of mining companies in South Africa. In an address at the [[Oxford Union]] in November 2015, Malema spoke out against billionaire mining company owner Patrice Motsepe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|title=Business Day|website=www.bdlive.co.za|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229135821/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|archivedate=29 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|title=Patrice Motsepe has no power\u201a says Malema|last=Jordaan|first=Buchule Raba And Nomahlubi|website=Times LIVE|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127215142/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|archivedate=27 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Further protests in 2015, the EFF delivered demands that included the socialization of the mining sector and called for more explicit targets for the 26% BEE ownership required by law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|title=Yes and no to EFF\u2019s list of demands|last=John|first=Victoria|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050240/http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|archivedate=28 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The EFF is a vocal proponent of expanding the role of [[State-owned enterprises of South Africa|South African state owned enterprises]] in the country's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techfinancials.co.za/2019/02/03/eff-wants-state-to-create-ai-robotics-and-biotechnology-firms/|title=EFF Wants State To Create AI, Robotics And BioTechnology Firms|last=Lourie|first=Gugu|date=2019-02-03|website=TechFinancials|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/the-effs-2019-election-manifesto-iv|title=The EFF`s 2019 election manifesto (IV) - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>\n\nMalema addressed a crowd in Marikana, Rustenburg in the platinum mining area, blaming mining companies and calling out platinum mining company Lonmin in particular, for poverty in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|title=SABC News - Malema blames mining companies for high levels of poverty:Thursday 7 July 2016|last=Tatai|first=Sello|website=www.sabc.co.za|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127232029/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|archivedate=27 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe party supports the re-introduction of the [[Capital punishment in South Africa|death penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|title=iafrica.com Juju wants death penalty|website=News.iafrica.com|accessdate=2016-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901181605/http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|archivedate=1 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|title=Malema wants death penalty #EFFlaunch &#124; Economic Freedom Fighters - EFF|publisher=Economic Freedom Fighters|date=2013-10-13|accessdate=2016-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126014743/http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|archivedate=26 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, after [[2016 South African municipal elections|local elections]] in South Africa, the EFF has suggested that they will back the Democratic Alliance in hung-metro areas, but would not be entering into a coalition with any political party in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|title=Malema says the EFF won't form coalitions, but will support DA in hung metros|last=Feltham|first=Luke|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=2016-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050103/http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|archivedate=28 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was the only parliamentary party that opposed the 2018 political party funding bill.<ref name=\"citizenFundingRejectionReasons\">https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1871025/reasons-why-the-eff-rejects-the-political-party-funding-bill/</ref>\n\n==High-profile members==\nHigh-profile members of the Central Command Team include [[Floyd Shivambu]], [[Fana Mokoena]] and [[Mbuyiseni Ndlozi]] (National Spokesperson).<ref name=\"EFF Central Command\">{{cite web|author=Economic Freedom Fighters|title=Central Command Team|url=http://www.effonline.org/structure|publisher=effonline.org|accessdate=21 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812200344/http://effighters.org.za/structure/officials/|archivedate=12 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Controversial businessman [[Kenny Kunene]] joined the Central Command Team in July 2013 before resigning from the Central Command Team on 20 August 2013 and from the organisation on 26 August 2013.<ref name=\"Sushi\">{{cite news|title='Sushi King' quits EFF leadership|author=Poloko Tau|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|newspaper=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|date=21 August 2013|accessdate=24 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824143456/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|archivedate=24 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ExitKunene\">{{cite news|title=Kunene quits EFF|author=[[South African Press Association|SAPA]]|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|newspaper=[[News24]]|date=26 August 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829084845/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|archivedate=29 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 4 November 2013, it was announced that [[Dali Mpofu]] had left the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) after 33 years of membership and joined the EFF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|title=Dali Mpofu joins EFF - Cape Times|publisher=IOL.co.za|date=2013-11-04|accessdate=2013-11-23|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202233822/http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|archivedate=2 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Musician and actress [[Ntando Duma]] also publicly pledged allegiance to EFF in February 2019.\n\n==Support base==\nAccording to a November 2013 [[Ipsos]] survey, the party's supporters are younger than average, with 49% being younger than 24, overwhelmingly black (99%) and mostly male, with women representing only 33% of the support base. A disproportionate number of supporters live in Malema's home province of [[Limpopo]] (28%), while only 1% live in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], a more populous province.<ref name=ipsos>{{cite web|title=The supporter profiles of SA`s three largest parties|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|publisher=Politicsweb|accessdate=6 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222022154/http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A 2018 survey conducted by social research company Citizen Surveys found that around 70% of EFF supporters were between the ages of 18 - 34, overwhelmingly black (97%), mostly based in major metropolitan cities (48%), predominantly male (62%) with 43% of their support base located in [[Gauteng|Gauteng Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizensurveys.net/citizen-surveys-how-many-white-eff-supporters-exist-and-11-other-stats/|title=Citizen Surveys: How many white EFF supporters exist, and 11 other stats|last=|first=|date=1 November 2018|website=Citizen Surveys|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nThe party was expected to make an impact in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], taking between 4 per cent and 8 per cent of the national vote. This was potentially enough for the party to hold [[Balance of power (parliament)|the balance of power]] in provinces where the governing African National Congress was in danger of losing its absolute majority.<ref name=\"irishtimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|title=Economic Freedom Fighters on rise in South Africa|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=6 May 2014|newspaper=The Irish Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506162746/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|archivedate=6 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The ANC retained is absolute majority whilst the EFF got 6.35% of the vote in the 2014 election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|title=ANC wins 249 seats|last=|first=|date=2014-05-12|website=News24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512215131/http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|archive-date=12 May 2014|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===National elections===\n====National Assembly====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total votes\n!Share of vote\n!Seats \n!+/\u2013\n!Government\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]<ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\">{{Cite web|title=2014 National and Provincial Elections Results - 2014 National and Provincial Election Results|url=http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|publisher=IEC|accessdate=11 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510231542/http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|archivedate=10 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|1,169,259\n|6.35%\n|{{Composition bar|25|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 25\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|1,881,521\n|10.79%\n|{{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 19\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|}\n\n====National Council of Provinces====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total # of<br/>seats won\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|{{Composition bar|7|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 7\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|{{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|}\n\n===Municipal elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n![[2016 South African municipal elections|2016]]<ref name=\"iec_summary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|title=Results Summary - All Ballots|publisher=elections.org.za|accessdate=11 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808191111/http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|archivedate=8 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|3,202,679\n|8.31%\n|-\n|}\n\n===Provincial elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n!rowspan=2|Election<br><ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\"/><ref name=\"dash\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.org.za/NPEDashboard/app/dashboard.html|title=Results Dashboard|website=www.elections.org.za|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n!colspan=2|[[Eastern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Free State (province)|Free State]]\n!colspan=2|[[Gauteng]]\n!colspan=2|[[KwaZulu-Natal|Kwazulu-Natal]]\n!colspan=2|[[Limpopo]]\n!colspan=2|[[Mpumalanga]]\n!colspan=2|[[North West (South African province)|North-West]]\n!colspan=2|[[Northern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Western Cape]]\n|- \n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|3.48%||2/63\n|8.15%||2/30\n|10.30%||8/73\n|1.85%||2/80\n|10.74%||6/49\n|6.26%||2/30\n|13.21%||5/33\n|4.96%||2/30\n|2.11%||1/42\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|7.84%||5/63\n|12.58%||4/30\n|14.69%||11/73\n|9.71%||8/80\n|14.43%||7/49\n|12.79%||4/30\n|18.36%||6/33\n|9.71%||3/30\n|4.04%||2/42\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\nOn 6 August 2015 the EFF announced that it has secured a Constitutional court case for its [[Jacob Zuma]] campaign of \"#PayBackTheMoney\". The case was heard on the 9 February 2016. The Judgement was released by Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng. The judgement stated that The President has violated the Constitution of South Africa, along with the [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker of the National Assembly]] [[Baleka Mbete]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} The President was given 60 days to fulfill the requirements of the Public Protector [[Thuli Madonsela]].<ref name=\"ZumaConCourt\">{{cite news|title=Lets meet in court, Malema tells Zuma|author=Emsie Ferreira|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=26 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201155340/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|archivedate=1 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2018 the EFF tabled a motion in The National Assembly to amend the Constitution so as to allow for the expropriation of land without compensation. The motion, brought by the EFF leader [[Julius Malema]], was adopted with a vote of 241 in support, and 83 against. The only parties who did not support the motion were the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], [[Freedom Front Plus]], [[Cope]] and the [[African Christian Democratic Party|ACDP]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Land Expropriation is one of the EFF's Seven cardinal pillars.<ref name=\"LandExpropriation\">{{cite news|title=National Assembly adopts motion on land expropriation without compensation|author=Jan Gerber|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|date=27 February 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920012156/https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|archivedate=2018-09-20|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the student wing of the EFF, the EFF Student Command won many universities across the country. The red berets defeated the ANC-aligned [[South African Students Congress]] (Sasco) at the [[Durban University of Technology]], the [[University of Zululand]] and [[Mangosuthu University of Technology]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} They also won in Cape Town, the District Six, Mowbray and Bellville [[Cape Peninsula University of Technology]] (CPUT) campuses with landslide victories, meaning they now are in charge of the institution's SRC. They also won the [[University of Cape Town]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Peter Keetse, president of the EFFSC, said the win was a warning shot for what was going to happen in 2019 national general elections. He said the youth were the influencers of the future, \u201ctherefore, this is an indication of what is to follow\u201d.<ref name=\"EFFStudentCommand\">{{cite news|title=Comrades see red as students back EFF on campus|author=Kwandokuhle Njoli|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sunday-tribune/news/comrades-see-red-as-students-back-eff-on-campus-17275465|date=30 September 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms and controversies==\nThe ANC has accused the Zimbabwean ruling party, the [[ZANU\u2013PF|Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] (ZANU\u2013PF), of supporting the EFF in order to destabilise the ANC.<ref name=\"bdliveMantashe\">{{cite news|title=Mantashe hits out at EFF for 'distorting the Freedom Charter'|author=Natasha Marrian|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|newspaper=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801072713/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|archivedate=1 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, a group of 17 former EFF members and councillors in the [[Northern Cape]] accused the party's senior leadership of corruption and sexual exploitation of more junior female party members.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2019199/expelled-eff-members-accuse-malema-shivambu-of-corruption-want-to-work-with-hawks/|title=Expelled EFF members accuse Malema, Shivambu of corruption, want to work with Hawks|last=reporter|first=Citizen|date=7 October 2018|work=The Citizen|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en}}</ref>  Four months later two former female employees of the EFF claimed that party leadership intimidated and engaged in acts of bullying behaviour towards them and other party staff members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/more-women-make-claims-of-eff-bullying-and-abuse-20190216|title=More women make claims of EFF bullying and abuse|last=Peter|first=Zamayirha|date=2019-02-16|website=CityPress|language=en|access-date=2019-02-22}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 a former member of the EFF's central command, Thembinkosi Rawula, accused senior party leaders of dictatorial leadership practices and of using party finances for personal benefit.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/disgruntled-eff-member-slams-malema-shivambu-for-taking-vbs-donation-party-denies-claims-20190405|title=Former EFF leader accuses Malema, Shivambu of taking VBS donation, party denies claims|last=Lizeka Tandwa and Tshidi Madia|date=2019-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> The EFF denied Rawula's accusation and stated that they would sue him for defamation as well as make the party's financials public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-to-sue-rawula-offers-journalists-access-to-effs-financial-records-20190410|title=Malema to sue Rawula, offers journalists access to EFF's financial records|last=Tandwa|first=Lizeka|date=2019-04-10|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was found guilty of [[Defamation|defamation of character]] in May 2019 by the South Gauteng High Court and ordered to pay R500,000 in damages to former Finance Minister [[Trevor Manuel]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-court-finds-effs-comments-about-trevor-manuel-defamatory-and-false/|title=Court vindicates Trevor Manuel in defamation battle with EFF|last=Quintal|first=Genevieve|date=30 May 2019|website=BusinessLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> Manuel brought the EFF and its leader, Julius Malema, to court after they alleged that the appointment of [[Edward Kieswetter]] as commissioner of SARS by Manuel was the result of nepotism.<ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/14/challenge-me-don-t-defame-manuel-to-eff-in-kieswetter-matter|title=Challenge me, don't defame - Manuel to EFF in Kieswetter nepotism matter|last=Modise|first=Kgomotso|website=ewn.co.za|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>  Following the judgement Manuel stated that he would be donating the R500,000 in damages to victims of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters#VBS Mutual Bank|VBS Mutual Bank scandal]] which the EFF is alleged to have participated in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fin24.com/Economy/trevor-manuel-i-dont-need-a-cent-of-eff-money-20190531-2|title=Trevor Manuel: I don't need a cent of EFF money|last=Khumalo|first=Sibongile|date=2019-05-31|website=Fin24|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>  \n\nFollowing a string of court case losses for inciting supporters to commit acts of either intimidation (against Karima Brown), land invasion ([[AfriForum]]) or of defamation of character (against Trevor Manuel) the party was left with combined court costs amounting to almost R1 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/courts/2144536/eff-wallows-in-legal-debt-of-almost-r1m/|title=EFF wallows in legal debt of almost R1m|last=Watson|first=Amanda|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>  \n\n===Alleged Corruption===\n\n==== Tenders ====\nA number of articles published by investigative journalists have accused the party of using their influence to earn improper payments from government suppliers in cities where the EFF has significant representative power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in \u2018kickbacks\u2019 in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>  An investigation by the [[amaBhungane]] centre for investigative journalism stated that the EFF received R500,000 in kickbacks from a company in return for a R1.26 billion contract to manage a fleet of vehicles used by the [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality|City of Johannesburg]] with tacit acquiescence of the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/firm-that-won-r1bn-joburg-fleet-contract-paid-malema-eff-slush-fund/|title=Firm that won R1bn Jo'burg fleet contract paid Malema-EFF 'slush-fund' - amaBhungane|last=Micah Reddy and Stefaans Br\u00fcmmer|date=29 November 2018|website=amabhungane.org|language=en-ZA|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/tender-comrades-part-1-trailing-the-juju-tractor/|title=Tender comrades part 1: Trailing the Juju tractor|website=amaBhungane|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Another investigation alleges that the party improperly benefited from the awarding of a fuel supply contract for the [[City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality|City of Tshwane]] netting the party R15 million from successful contractors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-29-tender-comrades-part-two-tshwane-tenderpreneurs-r15m-eff-tithe/|title=AMABHUNGANE: Tender Comrades Part Two: Tshwane tenderpreneur\u2019s R15m \u2018EFF tithe\u2019|last=amaBhungane|first=Stefaans Brummer & Micah Reddy for|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n====VBS Mutual Bank====\n{{See also|VBS Mutual Bank}}\nFollowing the publication of a [[South African Reserve Bank]] report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resbank.co.za/Lists/News%20and%20Publications/Attachments/8830/VBS%20Mutual%20Bank%20-%20The%20Great%20Bank%20Heist.pdf|title=The Great Bank Heist: Investigator's Report to the Prudential Authority|last=Motau|first=Terry|date=10 October 2018|website=South African Reserve Bank|page=135|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> into the collapse of [[VBS Mutual Bank]] implicating EFF deputy president Floyd Shivambu's brother media reports came out alleging that Shivambu received R10 million in illicit payments from VBS prior to it being placed under [[Receivership|curatorship]] in March 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-10-11-the-shivambu-brothers-and-the-great-vbs-heist/|title=The Shivambu Brothers and the Great VBS Heist|last=Van Wyk|first=Pauli|date=11 October 2018|work=[[Daily Maverick]]|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-10-12-00-pic-vbs-floyd-and-his-baby-brother|title=PIC, VBS, Floyd and his baby brother|last=Jika|first=Sabelo Skiti, Thanduxolo|date=12 October 2018|work=The M&G Online|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref> Prior to the publication of the Reserve Bank's report the EFF criticised the Reserve Bank for placing VBS under curatorship and accused it of victimising VBS on racial grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/single-post/2018/03/11/EFF-STATEMENT-ON-VBS-CURATORSHIP|title=EFF STATEMENT ON VBS CURATORSHIP {{!}} EFF: Economic Freedom Fighters|last=Ndlozi|first=Mbuyiseni Quintin|date=11 March 2018|website=Economic Freedom Fighters|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref> The EFF stated that it had seen no evidence that Shivambu received the R10 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-there-are-exchanges-of-money-between-floyd-and-brian-shivambu-but-floyd-did-not-get-money-from-vbs-says-eff/|title=Money was exchanged - but Floyd did not get any from VBS bank, says Malema|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> and called for government to recapitalise VBS Mutual Bank<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-calls-for-vbs-to-be-recapitalised-17501083|title=EFF calls for VBS to be recapitalised {{!}} IOL News|last=Zintle|first=Mahlati|date=16 October 2018|work=IOL|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> whilst also taking legal action against those mentioned in the Reserve Bank report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-malema-vbs-allegations-meant-to-discredit-the-eff/|title=Malema: VBS allegations meant to 'discredit the EFF'|last=Mvumvu|first=Zingisa|date=16 October 2018|work=Dispatch Live|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> A follow up investigation by the ''[[Daily Maverick]]'' alleged that the EFF illicitly received R1.8 million of VBS money through a network of proxy companies with the party's leadership (notably Shivambu and Malema) also illicitly receiving money though this network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-21-vbs-bank-heist-effs-family-ties-and-moneyed-connections/|title=VBS bank heist: EFF's family ties and moneyed connections|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=21 November 2018|work=Daily Maverick|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> After being approached by the ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'' for comment on his personal financial expenses Floyd Shivambu admitted that money from VBS, channeled through his brother, was used to buy his [[Range Rover Sport]] valued at R680,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-09-26-vbss-r680k-paid-for-floyds-wheels/|title=VBS\u2019s R680k paid for Floyd\u2019s wheels|last=Skiti|first=Thanduxolo Jika, Sabelo|website=The M&G Online|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nA follow up investigation by the ''Daily Maverick'' found that R454,000 of VBS money was used to pay for the 2017 EFF birthday celebration.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-27-cruising-nicely-on-vbs-effs-parties-lies-and-looted-money/|title=SCORPIO: 'Cruising nicely' on VBS: EFF's Parties, Lies and Looted Money|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> It also found that a total of R16.1 million was channeled through a Shivambu associated company largely for the benefit of the EFF.<ref name=\":5\" /> An additional investigation traced financial statements from an account that received VBS funds and allegedly controlled by Julius Malema; leading the author of the investigation to estimate that Malema received and directly benefited from R5.3-million illegally taken from VBS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-08-vbs-theft-money-laundering-lifes-little-luxuries-julius-malemas-time-of-spending-dangerously/|title=SCORPIO: VBS Theft, Money Laundering & Life's Little Luxuries: Julius Malema's time of spending dangerously|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=8 September 2019|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> Additional media reports in October 2019 alleged that the party received R4 million of VBS funds into a slush fund that was channeled to Malema via a company named Santaclara Trading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2190574/over-r4m-in-concerning-payments-made-into-malema-slush-fund-report/|title=Over R4m in 'concerning' payments made into Malema slush fund \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-10-13-julius-malemas-slush-fund-exposed/|title=Julius Malema's 'slush fund' exposed|website=TimesLIVE|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-linked-to-another-company-that-had-a-vbs-loan-report-20191013|title=Malema linked to another company that had a VBS loan - report|date=2019-10-13|website=News24|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nA former member of the EFF's leadership accused the party leadership of accepting donations from VBS Mutual Bank prior to its collapse.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMalema later forwarded a [[conspiracy theory]] that the VBS collapse was part of a plot intended to damage the EFF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-vbs-was-meant-to-collapse-and-finish-eff-malema-20190503|title=WATCH: 'VBS was meant to collapse and finish EFF' \u2013 Malema|date=2019-05-03|website=News24|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===Ideology===\nFeminists and the [[National Union of Metalworkers of South Africa]] have criticised the party's militarism and \"military command structure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179#.Usa_NvQW3Y5|title=Numsa wary of \u2018capitalist\u2019 Malema|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103182553/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179|archive-date=3 January 2014|author=Shanti Aboobaker|work=Sunday Independent|date=29 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen/|title=EFF & the Return of the Warrior Citizen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410024005/http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen|archive-date=10 April 2014|author=Siphokazi Magadla|work=Thought Leader|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2016 a group calling themselves \"Anonymous Africa\", claiming to be associated with the [[Hacktivism|hacktivist]] group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]], perpetrated a [[Denial-of-service attack|DDoS attack]] on the EFF's website stating the reason for the attack was the party's \"nationalist socialist rhetoric\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|title=EXCLUSIVE: Why Anonymous 'hacked' the SABC, Gupta websites|website=Fin24|access-date=2016-06-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617140057/http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|archivedate=17 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[South African Communist Party]] also condemns this party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacp.org.za/main.php?ID=5299|title=SACP supports ANC, condemns Julius Malema`s propagation of war in the strongest possible terms, calls on the police ?to act swiftly in terms of the rule of law|website=www.sacp.org.za|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n===Violence and bigotry===\nVusi Khoza, the party's candidate for [[Premier of KwaZulu-Natal]], has a criminal conviction for his involvement in what was believed to be a [[Xenophobia in South Africa|xenophobic attack]] on foreigners at Albert Park, [[Durban]] in December 2009.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164#.Uy0Y3vmSzY4 EFF\u2019s KZN man has criminal past] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091149/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164 |date=22 March 2014 }}, BHEKI MBANJWA, ''The Daily News'', 2014</ref>\n\nFeminists have characterised leading members of the party as [[Misogyny|misogynist]].<ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me/ Floyd Shivambu: Despicable Me] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224084746/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me |date=24 December 2013 }}, Sipho Hlongwane, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ Remembering Thomas Sankara, the EFF\u2019s muse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224094726/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ |date=24 December 2013 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/ Elections Analysis: The Economic Freedom Fighters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322090232/http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/|date=22 March 2014}}, Sonja Bornman, ''Feminist SA'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape EFF: Two senior party officials accused of involvement in 2008 gang rape] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091542/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape |date=22 March 2014 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2014, eight members of the EFF were forcibly removed from the legislature after their attire of red overalls carrying the slogan \"asijiki\" (meaning \"we are not turning back\") was found to be inappropriate by presiding officer, Ntombi Mekgwe.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.enca.com/eff-kicked-out-gauteng-legislature |title=EFF kicked out of Gauteng Legislature |publisher=enca.co.za |date=2014-07-01 |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref> Hundreds of EFF members protested against the ruling on 22 July near the legislature building.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ewn.co.za/2014/07/22/EFF-storm-Gauteng-Provincial-Legislature |title=EFF storm Gauteng Provincial Legislature |publisher=ewn.co.za |date=2014-07-24 |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref>\n\nIn February, 2016, during [[FeesMustFall|violent university protests]] characterised by arson and vandalism, EFF Youth leader Omphile Seleke posted instructions for making petrol bombs on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|title=EFF\u2019s \u2018petrol bomb recipe\u2019 fuels Tuks fears|last=de Lange|first=Ilse|date=2016-02-29|work=The Citizen|access-date=2017-04-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414081535/http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|archivedate=14 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, EFF Deputy President [[Floyd Shivambu]] congratulated the party supporters for causing damage to various [[H&M]] stores<ref>{{cite tweet|number=952114009448304640|user=FloydShivambu|title=That @hm nonsense of a clothing store is now facing consequences for its racism.|date=13 Jan 2018}}</ref> across South Africa due to a picture of a young black child wearing a green hoodie reading, \"Coolest Monkey in the Jungle\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|title=H&M monkey hoodie sparks outrage for \"racist\" image - CBS News|date=2018-01-08|work=[[CBS News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108222136/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|title=H&M apologizes for using black child to sell 'coolest monkey' top|date=2018-01-08|work=[[CNN]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108143043/http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|title=H&M slammed as racist for 'monkey in the jungle' hoodie|date=2018-01-08|work=[[CNBC]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108165628/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|title=H&M is apologizing for a product image called out as racist - Quartz|date=2018-01-08|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108235715/https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|title=H&M apologises following backlash over 'racist' image of child model on website - The Independent|date=2018-01-08|work=[[The Independent]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108173805/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|title=H&M Faces Twitter Backlash for \"Racist\" Hoodie - Pret-a-Reporter|date=2018-01-08|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108095220/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-01-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[Vodacom]] store in [[Polokwane]] was damaged and looted by EFF members following a presentation by [[Corruption Watch (South Africa)|Corruption Watch]] at the 2018 Vodacom Awards which included an image depicting EFF leaders Malema and Shivambu as \"abusers of Democracy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/matter-now-closed-eff-vodacom-issue-joint-statement-following-unrest-20181204|title='Matter now closed' - EFF, Vodacom issue joint statement following unrest|last=Seleka|first=Ntwaagae|date=2018-12-04|website=News24|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mybroadband.co.za/news/business-telecoms/288272-why-vodacom-met-with-the-eff.html|title=Why Vodacom met with the EFF|last=Staff Writer|date=4 December 2018|website=mybroadband.co.za|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, after the SONA address in parliament by the SA President, EFF MP [[Marshall Dlamini]] physically assaulted a member of the presidential security team after a disagreement between EFF MPs and the security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-eff-mp-slaps-man-after-sona-20190208|title=EFF MP slaps man after SONA|last=Gerber|first=Jan|date=8 February 2019|website=www.news24.com|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n====Actions against journalists and the media====\nJournalist Ranjeni Munusamy lodged an affidavit in December 2018 detailing threatening remarks, intimidation, harassment and personal attacks made by party members, including Malema, towards her and other journalists<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanef.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Part-2.pdf|title=Supporting Affidavit: Navaranjeni Munusamy|last=Munusamy|first=Ranjeni|date=19 December 2018|website=South African National Editors Forum|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> targeted by the party. The affidavit was supported by the South African National Editors Forum and other notable South African journalists such as [[Max du Preez]], Pauli VanWyk, Adriaan Jurgens Basson, and Barry Bateman.<ref name=\":1\" /> The EFF denied any involvement in attacks on Munusamy and other journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-12-19-eff-denies-involvement-in-attacks-on-journalists/|title=EFF denies involvement in attacks on journalists|last=Shange|first=Naledi|date=19 December 2018|website=www.timeslive.co.za|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>{{quote box|quote=''\"We need to ask the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|IEC]] how such a party can be on the ballot box. It threatens journalists. It encourages its supporters to make rape threats and sexual assault threats. It wants to dictate what I can do as a journalist.\"''<br/>\u2014Karima Brown<ref name=\"KB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack|publisher=African News Agency|date=20 March 2016|accessdate=6 March 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306215040/https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|archivedate=6 March 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right}}\nSouth African political journalist Karima Brown was the target of verbal abuse and threats of violence by EFF supporters following the EFF's publication of her personal contact details. This led charges with the police and Equity Court being laid against the party amidst speculation that this instance might be in breach of South Africa's Electoral Code of Conduct. Parties in breach of the code risk having their registration to run in elections being revoked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack {{!}} IOL News|website=www.iol.co.za|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> Malema stated on the incident that journalists have no privileges whilst accusing Brown of being a state agent and denied that EFF supporters were making threatening remarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/how-do-you-hold-an-underground-editor-accountable-malema-on-karima-brown-matter-20190306|title='How do you hold an underground editor accountable ' \u2013 Malema on Karima Brown matter|date=2019-03-06|website=News24|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> The court found in favour of Brown and ruled that the EFF had contravened the South African electoral code by inciting its supports to harass Brown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-06-06-eff-court-losses-mount-as-karima-brown-wins-battle-but-faces-criticism-of-her-own/|title=REPORT: EFF court losses mount as Karima Brown wins battle, but faces criticism of her own|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the publication of an article by the amaBhungane Centre for investigative journalism looking into allegations of corruption by the EFF the party controversially announced that it would be banning both amaBhungane and the ''Daily Maverick'' from its public events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in 'kickbacks' in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-13-this-is-what-panic-looks-like/|title=Editorial: This is What Panic Looks Like|last=Maverick|first=Daily|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sanef-appalled-by-malemas-call-to-ban-amabhungane-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190913|title=Sanef 'appalled' by Malema's call to ban amaBhungane, Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events|date=2019-09-13|website=News24|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> and announced that they would be treated an enemies of the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-shall-treat-them-as-enemies-malema-bans-amabhungane-and-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190912|title=Malema bans amaBhungane and Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events: 'We shall treat them as enemies'|date=2019-09-12|website=News24|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 the EFF was forced to publicly apologies and pay damages following a Gauteng High Court judgment that the party had made and spread false allegations that two journalists, Thandeka Gqubule and Anton Harber, were apartheid era 'StratCom' agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-retracts-stratcom-agent-allegations-against-gqubule-and-harber-apologises-after-court-order-20200125|title=EFF retracts 'Stratcom agent' allegations against Gqubule and Harber, apologises after court order|date=2020-01-25|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-24-eff-ndlozi-have-twenty-four-hours-to-pay-damages-to-journalists/|title=NEWSFLASH: EFF, Ndlozi have twenty-four hours to pay damages to journalists|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n===Racial and ethnic prejudice===\nSince its establishment the EFF has made a number of controversial racially or ethnically based statements about a number of South African minority groups. The EFF is widely criticised for inciting and perpetuating racism.<ref>[http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899 The EFF and the Question of National Unity] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413154904/http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899|date=13 April 2014}}, Duncan, Jane, ''SACSIS WEBSITE'', 29 JAN, 2014</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|title=\u2018EFF must #PayBackTheMoney for damage to varsities\u2019|last=Sain|first=Raahil|date=2016-03-08|access-date=2017-04-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414162203/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \n\n====Anti-Indian prejudice====\nThe South African Minority Rights Equality Movement initiated a court case against Malema for inciting racial sentiment by stating that a \"majority of [[Indian South Africans|Indians]] are racist\" at an EFF Youth Day rally in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/group-to-take-juliusmalema-to-court-for-racist-rant-15526571|title=Group to take #JuliusMalema to court for racist rant {{!}} IOL News|last=Mngoma|first=Nosipho|date=18 June 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|publisher=The Mercury|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was criticised by the [[South African Council of Churches]], the [[Ahmed Kathrada Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/no-one-is-going-to-intimidate-us-eff-hits-back-at-clergy-and-ahmed-kathrada-foundation-20181122|title='No one is going to intimidate us' - EFF hits back at clergy and Ahmed Kathrada Foundation|work=News24|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> and the ANC<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-bullies-trying-to-hide-their-own-shenanigans-anc-chief-whip-mthembu-20181123|title='EFF bullies' trying to 'hide their own shenanigans' - ANC chief whip Mthembu|work=News24|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> for comparing Public Enterprises Minister [[Pravin Gordhan]] to a \"dog\" whilst protesting the [[The Judicial Commission of Inquiry into Allegations of State Capture|Zondo Commission]] inquiry into government corruption. The EFF also accused the anti-corruption investigators of being members of an \"[[Indian South Africans|Indian]] [[cabal]]\" commenting on the presence of Indian South African's making up the investigative team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://city-press.news24.com/Voices/indian-cabal-narrative-is-to-protect-the-looting-project-20181119|title=\u2018Indian cabal\u2019 narrative is to protect the looting project|work=CityPress|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-to-gordhan-i-am-not-scared-of-the-indian-cabal|title=Malema to Gordhan: I am not scared of the Indian cabal|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> The EFF also accused Gordhan and his daughter of corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-11-23-00-gordhan-decries-eff-attack-on-daughter/|title=Gordhan decries EFF attack on daughter|last=Smit|first=Sarah|website=The M&G Online|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> The EFF accusations were proven false<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Analysis/fact-checked-julius-malemas-charges-against-pravin-gordhan-20181128|title=FACT CHECKED: EFF's charges against Pravin Gordhan|last=Jean le Roux, Kyle Cowan, Pieter du Toit and Adriaan Basson|date=2018-11-28|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-29-snowbank-bleff-pravin-gordhan-and-the-imaginary-r675m-canadian-account/|title=SnowBank \u2013 BLEFF, Pravin Gordhan and the imaginary R6...|last=Poplak|first=Richard|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref> and Gordhan laid charge of defamation against Malema stating that the EFF's \"determined defence of corruption and the corrupt, using personal attacks, racism and alleged hate speech is not acceptable and must be challenged.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/pravin-gordhan-lays-defamation-charges-against-malema-18267798|title=Pravin Gordhan lays defamation charges against Malema {{!}} IOL News|last=Ndaba|first=Baldwin|date=26 November 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>  The Equality Court found that the EFF was not guilty of hate speech in its statements relating to Gordhan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/pravin-gordhan-vs-julius-malema-the-high-court-jud|title=Pravin Gordhan vs Julius Malema|last=Sutherland|first=Roland|date=31 October 2019|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-10-31-judge-slates-malemas-juvenile-rant-as-eff-leader-wins-case-against-gordhan/|title=Judge slates Malema's 'juvenile' rant as EFF leader wins case against Gordhan|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> EFF leadership and its supporters have been criticised for using Gordhan's second name, Jamnadas, as a racial [[Dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]] to highlight to his Indian ethnicity in a [[pejorative]] way and question his status as a South African on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-23-pravin-jamnadas-gordhan-a-case-study-when-your-name-is-weaponised-by-haters-on-twitter/|title=POPULIST DOG WHISTLES: Pravin Jamnadas Gordhan, a case study: When your name is weaponised on Twitter|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\nANC member and government minister [[Jackson Mthembu]] accused the EFF of being racist and having a \"deep-seated hatred\" for Indian South Africans whilst criticizing the party's pursuit of Gordhan whilst participating in a parliamentary debate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-07-17-of-course-you-are-racist-you-are-jackson-mthembu-tells-eff-mps/|title='Of course, you are racist. You are,' Jackson Mthembu tells EFF MPs|last=Makinana|first=Andisiwe|date=17 July 2019|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/cigarettes-corruption-and-racism-why-the-eff-hates-gordhan-according-to-jackson-mthembu-20190718|title=Cigarettes, corruption and racism: Why the EFF hates Gordhan, according to Jackson Mthembu|last=van Diemen|first=Ethan|date=2019-07-18|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n====Anti-white prejudice====\nMalema stated at a political rally in 2016 that \u201cWe are not calling for the slaughter of [[White South Africans|white people]]\u201a at least for now\". When asked for comment by a news agency, the ANC spokesperson, Zizi Kodwa stated that there will be no comment from the ANC, as \"[h]e [Malema] was addressing his own party supporters.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Malema slammed for comments on whites|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|accessdate=30 May 2017|publisher=ENCA|date=8 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417053045/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While still the ANCYL leader, Malema was taken to the [[Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimination Act, 2000|Equality Court]] by [[AfriForum]] for repeatedly singing \u201c[[Dubul' ibhunu|dubul\u2019 ibhunu]]\u201d, which translate as \u201cshoot the [[boer]] [white farmer]\u201d. The ANC supported Malema, though AfriForum and the ANC reached a settlement before the appeal case was due to be argued in the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\n\nSouth Africa's [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] disqualified EFF councillor Thabo Mabotja in the 2016 local elections due a [[Twitter|tweet]] made by Mabotja calling for violence against white South Africans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|title=IEC disqualifies EFF councillor for racist tweet|date=2016-08-29|work=eNCA|access-date=2017-04-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414082702/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/elections/news/eff-councillor-candidate-disqualified-after-calling-for-whites-to-be-hacked-and-killed-reports-20160729|title=EFF councillor candidate disqualified after calling for whites to be 'hacked and killed' reports|date=2016-07-29|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> The EFF welcomed the commission's decision and renounced Mabotja.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/hes-on-his-own-juju-says-of-mabotja|title='He's on his own' Juju says of Mabotja|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/electoral-court-right-to-give-thabo-mabotja-the-ch|title=Electoral Court right to give Thabo Mabotja the chop|last=|first=|date=|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n\nJulius Malema, leader of the Economic Freedom Fighters, stated at a political rally in 2018 that \"''Go After A White Man... We Are Cutting The Throat Of Whiteness\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-are-cutting-the-throat-of-whiteness-malema-on-plans-to-remove-trollip-20180304|title='We are cutting the throat of whiteness' \u2013 Malema on plans to remove Trollip|work=News24|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>'' This led to the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] accusing the EFF's leader, Malema, of [[racism]] and not sharing the more tolerant views of South Africans broadly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/south-africans-dont-share-malemas-racist-views-maimane-13714966|title=South Africans don't share Malema's racist views - Maimane {{!}} IOL News|access-date=2018-03-11}}</ref> The EFF later stated that the reference to the \"throat of whiteness\" was a metaphorical reference to destroying [[white privilege]] and was not referring or advocating harm to white people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2019-03-28-empty-analysis-will-not-deter-the-eff-from-its-core-task-reaching-out-to-the-electorate/|title=OPINIONISTA: Empty analysis will not deter the EFF from its core task \u2014 reaching out to the electorate|last=Thambo|first=Sinawo|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of former Zimbabwean President [[Robert Mugabe]] EFF leader Julius Malema tweeted a number of controversial quotes from the late Mugabe that were interpreted as racially prejudiced towards white people.  Most notable was the quote that \"''The only white man you can trust is a dead white man''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-09-17-yep-its-hate-speech-says-sahrc-on-julius-malemas-dead-white-man-tweet/|title=Yep, it's hate speech, says SAHRC on Julius Malema's 'dead white man' tweet|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-15-malemas-mugabe-closing-gambit/|title=ANALYSIS: Malema\u2019s Mugabe closing gambit|last=Grootes|first=Stephen|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>  The [[South African Human Rights Commission]] (SAHRC) condemned the quote and stated that they would be taking Malema to court for allegedly spreading [[hate speech]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahrc.org.za/index.php/sahrc-media/news-2/item/2137-sahrc-to-take-malema-to-court-for-hate-speech|title=SAHRC to take Malema to court for hate speech|last=|first=|date=19 September 2019|website=South African Human Rights Commission|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Namibian Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n*[[Socialist Party of Azania]]\n*[[Workers and Socialist Party]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|last1=Van Onselen|first1=Gareth|title=Malema steals young communists' thunder|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q7p7lAID?url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|archivedate=6 June 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Pillay|first1=Verashni|title=EFF: You want land, a loan? You got it|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Mail & Guardian|date=21 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328111438/http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|archivedate=28 March 2014|url-status=live}}\n*Julius Malema (preface), [https://archive.org/details/EconomicFreedomFighters2014ElectionsManifesto ''EFF 2014 Elections Manifesto,''] Economic Freedom Fighters.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.effonline.org Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140918100051/http://effighters.org.za/ Old official website]\n*[http://economicfreedomfighters.org/ Supporter website]\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{South Africa political parties}}\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters| ]]\n[[Category:African and Black nationalist organizations in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalist political parties]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics]]\n[[Category:Political parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2013]]\n[[Category:National liberation movements in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-white racism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-Indian sentiment in Africa]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Left-wing populist parties]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo in Omphile's name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_Freedom_Fighters"}
{"title_page": "Paul Feig", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor and filmmaker|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{pp-pc1}}{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name= Paul Samuel Feig\n| image = Paul Feig in London.jpg\n| caption = Feig in 2018\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|9|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Mount Clemens, Michigan]], U.S.\n| occupation = Filmmaker, actor\n| years_active = 1986\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|Laurie Karon|1994}}\n}}\n\n'''Paul Samuel Feig''' ({{IPAc-en|f|i\u02d0|\u0261}};<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2012/01/oscar-qa-paul-feig-bridesmaids-sequel-kristen-wiig-melissa-mccarthy|title=Paul Feig on the BridesmaidsSequel, Female Comedy, and His S.N.L. Dreams|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=28 January 2016|publisher=Vanity Fair|first=Krista|last=Smith}}</ref> born September 17, 1962) is an American actor and filmmaker. He is best known for directing films starring frequent collaborator [[Melissa McCarthy]], including ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]'' (2011), ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'' (2013), ''[[Spy (2015 film)|Spy]]'' (2015), and ''[[Ghostbusters (2016 film)|Ghostbusters]]'' (2016). He also directed the black comedy mystery film ''[[A Simple Favor (film)|A Simple Favor]]'' (2018) and the romantic comedy film ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'' (2019).\n\nFeig created the comedy series ''[[Freaks and Geeks]]'' (1999\u20132000) and ''[[Other Space]]'' (2015). He has also directed several episodes of the U.S version of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'' and ''[[Nurse Jackie]]'', as well as episodes of ''[[Mad Men]]'', ''[[30 Rock]]'', and ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''. He received nominations for two [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] for writing on ''Freaks and Geeks'' and three for directing on ''The Office''.\n\nAs an actor, Feig is best known for playing Tim the Camp Counselor in the comedy film ''[[Heavyweights]]'' (1995). He also starred as Bobby Wynn in the sitcom ''[[The Jackie Thomas Show]]'' (1992\u201393) and as Mr. Eugene Pool on the sitcom ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina, the Teenage Witch]]'' (1996\u201397).\n\n==Early life==\nFeig was born in and raised in [[Mount Clemens, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/movies/2014/10/09/ghostbusters-paul-feig/16966003/|title=Michigan's Paul Feig to direct female-led 'Ghostbusters'|date=October 9, 2014|author=Associated Press|website=[[Detroit Free Press]]|accessdate=January 23, 2015}}</ref> His mother, Elaine Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Artingstall), was a telephone operator, and his father, Sanford William Feig, owned Ark Surplus on [[Gratiot Avenue]].<ref name=nyt1>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/28/magazine/28feig-t.html|title=The Trouble With Paul Feig|date=28 September 2008|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytribune.com/articles/2011/07/29/life/doc4e3316585d1d5916009670.txt|title=Director Paul Feig is a genius at portraying awkwardness|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Tyk_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=Z1AMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5972,617438&dq=personally%20feig%20artingstall&hl=en|title=The Windsor Star - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref> Feig's father was born [[Jewish]] and converted to [[Christian Science]]; Feig's parents met at a church social, and Feig was also raised in Christian Science.<ref name=nyt1/><ref>{{cite web|last=Robert |first=Daniel |url=http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/1946/Paul-Feig-director-of-Unaccompanied-Minors-/ |title=Interviews > Paul Feig Director Of Unaccompanied Minors |publisher=Suicidegirls.com |date=2006-05-04 |accessdate=2012-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/9428508/qa-bridesmaids-heat-director-paul-feig|title=The King of the Lady Gross-out|first=Mary Kaye|last=Schilling|date=28 June 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1986\u20132010: Early career, ''Freaks and Geeks'' and directorial debut===\nAfter a year at [[Wayne State University]], Feig moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and transferred to the [[University of Southern California]]. He also worked as a tour guide at [[Universal Studios Hollywood]], embarked on a [[stand-up comedy]] act, and landed minor roles on various television shows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/28/magazine/28feig-t.html|title=The Trouble With Paul Feig|last=Bowe|first=John|publisher=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|date=September 26, 2008}}</ref> Feig also appeared in a number of films, such as ''[[Ski Patrol (1990 film)|Ski Patrol]]'',<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE5DE103AF930A25752C0A966958260|title=Ski Patrol (1989) Review/Film; Meanwhile, Pops Is Back At the Lodge|author=James, Caryn|authorlink=Caryn James|date=January 13, 1990}}</ref> and in a role alongside [[Ben Stiller]] in the 1995 film ''[[Heavyweights]]'', in which he played camp counselor Tim. On the first season of ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina, the Teenage Witch]]'', Feig portrayed Mr. Eugene Pool, [[Sabrina Spellman|Sabrina]]'s science teacher.\n\nWith ''Heavyweights'' co-scripter [[Judd Apatow]], Feig created the short-lived comedy series ''[[Freaks and Geeks]]'', inspired by his experiences at [[Chippewa Valley High School]] in [[Clinton Township, Macomb County, Michigan|Clinton Township]], [[Michigan]]. The show aired on [[NBC]] during the 1999\u20132000 television season. Eighteen episodes were completed, but the series was canceled after only twelve had aired. Despite the short run, ''Freaks and Geeks'' has since maintained a devoted cult following. The show was named in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's 100 Greatest Shows of All Time,<ref>{{cite news|last=Poniewozik |first=James |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/completelist/0,,1651341,00.html |title=The Abbott and Costello Show &#124; All-TIME 100 TV Shows &#124; Entertainment |publisher=TIME.com |date=2007-09-06 |accessdate=2012-03-28}}</ref> and in summer 2008, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' ranked ''Freaks and Geeks'' as the 13th best show of the past 25 years.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207339,00.html |title=The New Classics: TV &#124; TV |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=2012-03-20 |accessdate=2012-03-28 |first=Kelly |last=Connolly}}</ref> Feig was nominated for two Emmys for writing the show's pilot and the season finale.\n\nFeig made his directorial debut with the drama film ''[[I Am David (film)|I Am David]]'', which premiered at the 2003 [[Cannes Film Festival]]. He later directed the Christmas comedy film ''[[Unaccompanied Minors]]'' (2006). \n\n===2011\u20132016: ''Bridesmaids'', ''The Heat'', ''Spy'' and ''Ghostbusters''===\nIn 2011, Feig was consulted to direct the Apatow-produced comedy film ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]''. Written by [[Annie Mumolo]] and [[Kristen Wiig]], the plot centers on Annie (Wiig), who suffers a series of misfortunes after being asked to serve as [[maid of honor]] for her best friend, Lillian, played by [[Maya Rudolph]].<ref name=\"NYT Obit\">{{cite news| author = Fox, Margalit| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/06/arts/06clayburgh.html| title = Jill Clayburgh Dies at 66; Starred in Feminist Roles| work = [[The New York Times]]| date = November 5, 2010}}</ref> Budgeted at $32.5 million, ''Bridesmaids'' was both critically and commercially successful, eventually grossing over $288 million worldwide, and served as a touchstone for discussion about women in comedy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bridesmaids_2011/ | title=Bridesmaids (2011) | publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bridesmaids-effect-why-female-comedies-203160/ | title='Bridesmaids' Effect: Why Female Comedies Are Making Comeback | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> The film was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and received multiple other accolades, including [[Academy Award]] nominations in the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for [[Melissa McCarthy]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Wiig and Mumolo.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thirdage.com/news/bridesmaids-breathes-life-into-womens-comedy_05-15-2011/ | title='Bridesmaids' Breathes Life into Women's Comedy | website=[[Third Age]] | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> \n\nIn 2013, Feig reunited with McCarthy on [[buddy cop]] [[action comedy]] film ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'', also starring [[Sandra Bullock]]. Directed by Feig and written by [[Katie Dippold]], it centers on a mismatched police pairing who must overcome their differences in order to take down a mobster. The film received generally positive reviews from critics, who praised the chemistry, and performances of Bullock and McCarthy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/Critics-Consensus-White-House-Down-Is-Predictable-Action-Fluff/|title=Critics Consensus: White House Down Is Predictable Action Fluff|first=Tim|last=Ryan|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=June 28, 2013|accessdate=August 27, 2017}}</ref> and was a success at the box office, grossing $229 million worldwide against a $43 million budget.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=The Heat (2013) - Box Office Mojo|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bullockmccarthy.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=June 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Feig wrote, directed, and produced the spy comedy movie ''[[Spy (2015 film)|Spy]]'' for [[20th Century Fox]], again starring Melissa McCarthy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Paul Feig Developing Female James Bond Comedy 'Susan Cooper'|url=http://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/paul-feig-developing-female-james-bond-comedy-susan-cooper-98196|accessdate=21 February 2014|newspaper=thewrap.com|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> It follows the life of a secret agent, Susan Cooper, trying to expose the black-market. The film received acclaim from critics and became another box office success at an international gross of $235.7 million.<ref name=\"jagran\">{{cite news|title='Spy' - Movie Review|url=http://post.jagran.com/spy-movie-review-1434705464|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref> It was nominated for two [[Golden Globe Award]]s: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for McCarthy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travers|first1=Peter|title=Spy Review|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/spy-20150603|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, Feig produced the animated feature ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]'' for [[Blue Sky Studios]], based on the ''[[Peanuts]]'' comic strip and characters created by [[Charles M. Schulz]].<ref name=\"jagran\"/> That same year, it was announced that Feig will direct a film adaptation of [[Play-Doh]]s for [[Hasbro Studios]], 20th Century Fox, and [[Chernin Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/play-doh-live-action-feature-paul-feig-fox-hasbro-1201403854/|title=Fox Molding \u2018Play-Doh\u2019 Film With Paul Feig Circling; Another Hasbro Toy Brand Making Movie Transfer|publisher=Deadline|last=Fleming, Jr|first=Mike|date=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2015, Feig also created the science fiction comedy series ''[[Other Space]]'' for [[Yahoo!]]'s [[video on demand]] service [[Yahoo! Screen]] and wrote the show's first episode. The series stars [[Trace Beaulieu]], [[Neil Casey]], [[Eugene Cordero]], [[Joel Hodgson]], [[Conor Leslie]], [[Bess Rous]], [[Karan Soni]], and [[Milana Vayntrub]] as the dysfunctional crew of an exploratory spaceship who become trapped in an unknown universe. ''Other Space'' received positive reviews,<ref>{{cite web|title=Other Space: Season 1| url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/other-space/s01/| publisher=Rotten Tomatoes| accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/other-space |title=Other Space : Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref> but was not renewed for a second season due to Yahoo! Screen being shut down in 2016. Feig would later create a [[Tumblr]] to provide direct links to each episode after he reobtained the rights to the series.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://io9.gizmodo.com/its-finally-easy-to-watch-other-space-the-best-scifi-c-1791820879| title= It's Finally Easy to Watch Other Space, the Best Scifi Comedy You've Never Seen| first= James | last= Whitbrook | website= io9.com| date= January 31, 2017 | accessdate= June 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Feig directed and co-wrote the [[Ghostbusters (2016 film)|female driven reboot]] of the ''[[Ghostbusters]]'' franchise, starring McCarthy,  [[Kristen Wiig]],  [[Kate McKinnon]], and [[Leslie Jones (comedian)|Leslie Jones]] as four women who begin a [[Ghost hunting|ghost-catching]] business in New York City.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/10/08/paul-feig-ghostbusters-female | work=Entertainment Weekly | first=Esther | last=Zuckerman | title=Paul Feig explains his vision for a female-led 'Ghostbusters' | date=October 8, 2014}}</ref>  The announcement of the female-led cast in 2015 drew a polarized response from the public and Internet backlash,<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|author=Zack Sharf |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/ghostbusters-scene-change-internet-backlash-1201703854/ |title=\u2018Ghostbusters\u2019 Reboot Added New Scene As Reaction To Internet Backlash |publisher=IndieWire |date=2016-07-08 |accessdate=2017-02-08}}</ref> leading to the film's [[IMDb]] page and associated [[YouTube]] videos receiving low ratings prior to the film's release.<ref name=\"Hayes\">{{cite web|last1=Hayes|first1=Britt|title=\u2018Ghostbusters\u2019 Haters Spam IMDb With Low Ratings|url=http://screencrush.com/ghostbusters-imdb-what-the/|website=ScreenCrush|accessdate=19 November 2017|date=11 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Hickey\">{{cite web|last1=Hickey|first1=Walt|title=\u2018Ghostbusters\u2019 Is A Perfect Example Of How Internet Movie Ratings Are Broken|url=http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ghostbusters-is-a-perfect-example-of-how-internet-ratings-are-broken/|website=FiveThirtyEight|accessdate=8 February 2017|date=14 July 2016}}</ref> The film grossed $229 million worldwide against a production budget of $144 million, becoming the highest-grossing live-action comedy domestically of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Box Office Performance for Comedy Movies in 2016|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/market/2016/genre/Comedy|accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref> Due to its high production and marketing budget, it is considered a <!-- Please see discussion before editing this language. Local consensus has thus far favored 'bomb' as a neutral and accurate descriptor. -->[[box office bomb]].<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-box-office-masks-glut-of-big-budget-film-flops-1471192593|title=Rising Box Office Masks Glut of Big-Budget Film Flops|first=Ben|last=Fritz|date=August 14, 2016|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=September 1, 2016}}{{subscription required}}</ref> <!-- Please see discussion before adding information regarding critical reception. As review aggregators do not agree on the summary of reception, current consensus is against adding a general summary, per WP:OR and WP:SYNTH. -->\n\n===2017\u2013present: ''A Simple Favor'' and ''Last Christmas''===\nIn 2017, Feig produced [[Jonathan Levine]]'s comedy film ''[[Snatched (2017 film)|Snatched]]'', starring [[Amy Schumer]] and [[Goldie Hawn]] as a mother-daughter couple who are abducted while on vacation in South America.<ref name=Aug2015Deadline>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Director Jonathan Levine Circles Amy Schumer Mother-Daughter Comedy At Fox|url=http://deadline.com/2015/08/jonathan-levine-amy-schumer-mother-daughter-comedy-fox-1201501251/|accessdate=August 19, 2015|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=August 18, 2015}}</ref> The same year, he began production on the comedy thriller ''[[A Simple Favor (film)|A Simple Favor]]''. Based on the 2017 [[A Simple Favor (novel)|novel of the same name]] by Darcey Bell, it stars [[Anna Kendrick]], [[Blake Lively]], and [[Henry Golding]], and follows a small town blogger who tries to solve the disappearance of her mysterious and rich best friend. Released in September 2018, the film received generally favorable reviews from critics, with praise for the plot twists and performances of Kendrick and Lively.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Simple Favor (2018)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=asimplefavor.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=September 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Feig directed an advertisement for [[Diet Coke]] starring Hayley Magnus, which was shown during the [[Super Bowl commercials|Super Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web |date= February 5, 2018 |last= Steinberg |first= Brian |title= Inside Diet Coke\u2019s Return to Super Bowl Advertising |url= https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/super-bowl-commercials-2018-diet-coke-hayley-magnus-1202686849/ |website=Variety }}</ref> In 2019, he directed the romantic comedy ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'', reteaming with [[Henry Golding]], who starred in the film alongside [[Emilia Clarke]].\n\nIn March 2019, following 20th Century Fox's acquisition by [[The Walt Disney Company]], Feig announced he would be moving his Feigco production studio to [[Universal Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/fox-film-disney-paul-feig-universal-fox-layoffs-1202579443/|title=Fox Film Team Faces Rocky Disney Future; Paul Feig Moves Label To Universal|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=2019-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/paul-feig-feigco-entertainment-universal-fox-1203169663/|title=Paul Feig\u2019s Feigco Entertainment Jumps From Fox to First-Look Deal at Universal|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|last2=Donnelly|first2=Matt|date=2019-03-21|website=Variety |access-date=2019-03-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFeig has been married to Laurie Karon since September 23, 1994.{{cn|date=February 2020}}The couple has no children.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Film\n|-\n! width=65 |[[Film director|Director]]\n! width=65 |[[Film producer|Producer]]\n! width=65 |[[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|- \n| 2003\n| ''[[I Am David (film)|I Am David]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| [[List of directorial debuts|Directorial debut]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Unaccompanied Minors]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|\n|- \n| 2011\n| ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|\n|- \n| 2013\n| ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n| \n|- \n| 2015\n| ''[[Spy (2015 film)|Spy]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Ghostbusters (2016 film)|Ghostbusters]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|Executive}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Co-written with [[Katie Dippold]]\n|- \n| 2018\n| ''[[A Simple Favor (film)|A Simple Favor]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|- \n| 2019\n| ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|}\n\n'''Producer only'''\n* ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Snatched (2017 film)|Snatched]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Ferdinand (film)|Ferdinand]]'' (2017) (Uncredited)\n* ''[[Someone Great (film)|Someone Great]]'' (2019)\n\n====Acting roles==