ion = 1996 United States presidential election in Nevada\n| next_year = 1996\n| election_date = November 3, 1992\n| image_size = x160px\n| image1 = Bill Clinton.jpg\n| nominee1 = '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Arkansas]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Al Gore]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''4'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''189,148'''\n| percentage1 = '''37.36%'''\t\n| image2 = George H. W. Bush, President of the United States, 1989 official portrait (cropped 2).jpg\n| nominee2 = [[George H.W. Bush]] \n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Dan Quayle]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 175,828\n| percentage2 = 34.73%\t\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 132,580\t\n| percentage3 = 26.19%\n| map_image = Nevada Presidential Election Results by County, 1992.svg\n| map_size = 275px\n| map_caption = County Results\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Clinton'''\n{{legend|#d3e7ff|<40%}}\n{{legend|#b9d7ff|40-50%}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Bush'''\n{{legend|#ffccd0|<40%}}\n{{legend|#f2b3be|40-50%}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Perot'''\n{{legend|#b6ffa8|<40%}}\n{{col-end}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNV}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Nevada''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose four representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[United States presidential elections in Nevada|Nevada]] was won by [[List of governors of Arkansas|Governor]] [[Bill Clinton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Arkansas]]) with 37.36% of the popular vote over incumbent President [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Texas]]) with 34.73%. Businessman [[Ross Perot]] ([[Independent politician|I]]-Texas) finished in third, with 26.19% of the popular vote.<ref name=results/> Clinton ultimately won the national vote, defeating incumbent President Bush and Perot.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nClinton's win, although narrow, would mark the beginning of Nevada's transition from a safe Republican state into a [[swing state]]; in all three presidential elections held in the 1980s, Republicans had dominated Nevada by double digit margins and swept every county. Although Clinton carried only two of the state's seventeen counties, his win in [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]], where [[Las Vegas]] is located, and the most populous county in the state, would prove the key to this and future Democratic victories in Nevada.\n\nClinton's percentage of the vote was the lowest to win a state since Woodrow Wilson carried Idaho with only 31 percent of the vote in [[1912 United States presidential election in Idaho|1912]]. \n\n{{As of|2016|11|alt=As of [[2016 United States presidential election in Nevada|the 2016 presidential election]]}}, this is the last time a Democratic presidential candidate carried [[White Pine County, Nevada|White Pine County]] in a presidential election,<ref name=\"how\">Sullivan, Robert David; [http://www.americamagazine.org/content/unconventional-wisdom/how-red-and-blue-map-evolved-over-past-century \u2018How the Red and Blue Map Evolved Over the Past Century\u2019]; ''America Magazine'' in ''The National Catholic Review''; June 29, 2016</ref> and the last one where a third-party candidate carried any Nevada county. In this case, [[Ross Perot]] carried [[Storey County, Nevada|Storey County]].<ref name=\"how\"/>\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Nevada<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results \u2013 Nevada|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&fips=32&f=0&off=0&elect=0&minper=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Electoral votes\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]'''\n| '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''189,148'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''37.36%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''4'''\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| [[George H.W. Bush]] ([[incumbent]])\n| align=\"right\" | 175,828\n| align=\"right\" | 34.73%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DDDDDD; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| [[Ross Perot]]\n| align=\"right\" | 132,580\t\n| align=\"right\" | 26.19%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFA6C9; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Populist Party (United States, 1984)|America First]]\n| [[Bo Gritz|James \"Bo\" Gritz]]\n| align=\"right\" | 2,892\t\n| align=\"right\" | 0.57%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | ''