 birth_place = Peoria, IL\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = Writer\n| genre = Nonfiction\n| subject  = American culture and history\n| notableworks =\n\n| website    = {{URL|https://www.theattic.space/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bruce Watson''' (born August 17, 1953) is an American writer who specializes in American culture and history. He has written six books as well as feature articles, humorous essays, and book reviews for [[Smithsonian Magazine]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Articles by Bruce Watson |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/author/bruce-watson/ |website=Smithsonian Magazine |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> [[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Bruce Watson |url=https://www.americanheritage.com/users/bruce-watson |website=American Heritage |accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Reader's Digest]], [[The Washington Post]], [[The Los Angeles Times]], [[The Boston Globe]], [[The San Francisco Chronicle]], [[The Daily Hampshire Gazette]], [[Yankee Magazine]], [[Family Fun]], [[FamilyPC]], and other publications. Watson publishes an online magazine called ''The Attic'' that highlights true stories for a kinder, cooler America.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watson |first1=Bruce |title=the attic |url=https://www.theattic.space/ |website=The Attic |accessdate=December 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Richie |title=Out of the attic come tales of our traditions |url=https://www.recorder.com/Writer-s-blog-turns-to-American-portraits-13049805 |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |publisher=Greenfield Recorder |date=October 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Watson |first1=Bruce |title=A columnist ahead of his time: Bruce Watson says goodbye to the Bulletin after 28 years |url=https://www.amherstbulletin.com/Archives/2014/07/01artwatson-hg-080114 |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |agency=Amherst Bulletin |date=December 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nWatson was born on August 17, 1953 in [[Peoria, IL]] and grew up in [[Orange County, California]]. He studied creative writing at [[Pomona College]] from 1971-1973. He received a B.A. in journalism in 1976 fromthe [[University of California, Berkeley]], an Elementary Education credential from [[California State University San Francisco]] in 1981, a M.Ed. in Elementary Education, specializing in Math, Science, and Instructional Technology from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] in 1990, and a M.A. in American History from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] in 1995. He has taught at [[Deerfield Academy]], the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]], [[Bard College]], and [[Hampshire College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hampshire.academia.edu/BruceWatson/CurriculumVitae |website=Academia.edu |title= Bruce Edward Watson|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==The Attic==\nSince January 20, 2017, Watson has published an online magazine, The Attic \u2014 {{URL|https://www.theattic.space/}}. Watson conceived the site as a non-political response to the intensely partisan politics of our times.  \u201cI was tired of all the anger,\u201d he said. \u201cIt seemed like it was driving so much of the coverage and content in magazines and newspapers. At the same time, it felt like something was really being lost with our history. You have to know your country, know the past to move past all the anger.\u201d <ref>{{cite news |last1=Pfarrer |first1=Steve |title=Stories Worth Revisiting |url= https://www.gazettenet.com/Getting-away-from-the-partisan-battle-At-his-website-The-Attic--Bruce-Watson-celebrates-stories-of-shared-American-experience-32482912 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |publisher=Daily Hampshire Gazette |date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Attic, where Watson encourages readers to \u201crummage,\u201d is a collection of articles, lists, songs, and quotations, all promoting \u2018\u2019a kinder, cooler America.\u2019\u2019 These include articles about American Faces, American Places, American history, literature, and arts, women, humor, plus smaller sections on science and music. Though the site avoids current politics, it has profiled such reformers as New Deal Labor Secretary [[Francis Perkins]], United Farmworkers organizer [[Dolores Huerta]], and African-American icons [[Frederick Douglas]] and [[W.E.B. DuBois]].  \u201cI want Attic readers to be constantly surprised and inspired by what they find up there,\u2019\u2019 Watson said.\n\nThe Attic has 1,500 weekly subscribers, several thousand followers on social media, and readers in 97 countries and all 50 states. Among the American Faces featured in The Attic are poets [[Langston Hughes]], [[Tracy K. Smith]], and [[William Carlos Williams]], artists [[Jasper Johns]], [[Judy Chicago]]. and [[Jacob Lawrence]], novelists [[Jack Kerouac]] and [[Leslie Marmon Silko]], and humorists [[James Thurber]], [[Ogden Nash]], and [[Robert Benchley]]. \u2018\u2019Finding and writing about people who worked against the grain in some way or pushed back against hard times is always a pleasure,\u201d Watson said. <ref>Ibid.</ref>\n\nThe Attic\u2019s American Places reports on Watson\u2019s visits to such locales as [[Cadillac Ranch]], the [[Grand Coulee Dam]], [[Harpers Ferry]], WV, the [[Mark Twain House]], and Toad Suck, Arkansas. During the COVID-19 crisis, Watson is runnning a month-long feature on \u2018\u2019The Healers,\u2019\u2019 featuring the humanitarian work of [[Walt Whitman]], [[Lillian Wald]], [[Paul Farmer]], and others.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Attic|url= https://www.theattic.space/ |website=The Attic|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*''[[Light]]: A Radiant History from Creation to the Quantum Age'' (Bloomsbury, 2016).<ref>{{cite web |title=Light: A Radiant History |url=https://www.light-radiant.com/ |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lightman |first1=Alan |title=Mysteries of light through the ages |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/mysteries-of-light-through-the-ages/2016/02/19/9114a0c2-83e1-11e5-a7ca-6ab6ec20f839_story.html |accessdate=December 18, 2019 |publisher=Washington Post |date=February 19, 2016}}</ref>\n*''[[Freedom Summer]]: The Savage Season That Made Mississippi Burn and Made America a Democracy'' (Viking, 2010)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/bruce-watson/freedom-summer/ |title=FREEDOM SUMMER: The Savage Season that Made Mississippi Burn and Made America a Democracy |website=Kirkus Reviews |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garner |first1=Dwight |title=Mississippi Invaded by Idealism |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/19/books/19book.html |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |agency=New York Times |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Freedom Summer: The Savage Season That Made Mississippi Burn and Made America a Democracy |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-670-02170-3 |website=Publisher's Weekly |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wynn |first1=Ron |title=Freedom Summer: Bruce Watson |url=https://bookpage.com/reviews/6501-bruce-watson-freedom-summer-history#.XfVw8uhKjIU |website=BookPage |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lewis |first1=David Levering |title='Freedom Summer,' by Bruce Watson |url=https://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Freedom-Summer-by-Bruce-Watson-3260558.php |website=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Freedom Summer' due for release next month |url=https://www.meridianstar.com/archives/freedom-summer-due-for-release-next-month/article_c3b82310-f2e9-5e76-a05d-e23b1cd0ffee.html |accessdate=December 25, 2019 |agency=[[The Meridian Star]] |date=May 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Journey into Light |url=https://mountainenterprise.com/story/journey-into-light-218E/ |website=The Mountain Enterprise |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n*''[[Sacco and Vanzetti]]: The Men, The Murders, and The Judgment of Mankind'' (Viking, 2007).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grimes |first1=William |title=Prejudice and Politics: Sacco, Vanzetti and Fear |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/15/books/15grim.html |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |publisher=New York Times |date=August 15, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bruce Watson presents new book on Sacco & Vanzetti at the Boston Public Library |url=https://saccoandvanzetti.org/sn_display1.php?row_ID=29 |website=Sacco and Vanzetti Commemoration Society |accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rehm |first1=Diane |title=Bruce Watson: \"Sacco & Vanzetti\" (Viking) |url=https://dianerehm.org/shows/2007-08-22/bruce-watson-sacco-vanzetti-viking |website=Diane Rehm |accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Bread and Roses]]: Mills, Migrants, and The Struggle for the American Dream'' (Viking, 2005).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dixler |first1=Elsa |title='Bread and Roses': The Fruits of Labor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/28/books/review/bread-and-roses-the-fruits-of-labor.html |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |publisher=New York Times |date=August 28, 2005}}</ref>\n*''The Man Who Changed How Boys and Toys Were Made'' (Viking, 2002).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy |title=ANTIQUES; A Perfect Toy For a Nation Of Inventors |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/13/books/antiques-a-perfect-toy-for-a-nation-of-inventors.html |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |publisher=New York Times |date=December 13, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Yardley |first1=Jonathan |title=The Erector Set's Inventor, Working Hard at Play |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2002/11/14/the-erector-sets-inventor-working-hard-at-play/674f946b-53bd-434a-b19c-66c25ad53d63/ |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=November 14, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Susan |title=Boy Toy |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2002/1111/196.html#2f9f009c265c |website=Forbes |accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Coopee |first1=Todd |title=The Man Who Changed How Boys and Toys Were Made |url=https://toytales.ca/the-man-who-changed-how-boys-and-toys-were-made/ |website=Toy Tales |accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==eBooks==\n\n*''[[Jon Stewart]]: Beyond the Moments of Zen'' (New Word City, 2012).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watson |first1=Bruce |title=Jon Stewart: Beyond The Moments Of Zen |url=https://www.amazon.com/Jon-Stewart-Beyond-Moments-Zen-ebook/dp/B0093FPMVU |website=Amazon.com |publisher=New Word City, Inc |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*''[[Stephen Colbert]]: Beyond Truthiness'' (New Word City, 2014).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watson |first1=Bruce |title=Stephen Colbert: Beyond Truthiness |url=https://www.amazon.com/Stephen-Colbert-Truthiness-Bruce-Watson-ebook/dp/B00HYY3I18/ref=pd_sim_351_2/136-8300561-3776121?_encoding=UTF8&pd_rd_i=B00HYY3I18&pd_rd_r=b32c403c-82ce-414f-ad6c-9e96ddd661f0&pd_rd_w=PZrW0&pd_rd_wg=kBMly&pf_rd_p=04d27813-a1f2-4e7b-a32b-b5ab374ce3f9&pf_rd_r=HD5P2R8EJ8GAYW2FNFWS&psc=1&refRID=HD5P2R8EJ8GAYW2FNFWS |website=Amazon.com |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n*2017 ''Light'' was nominated for a [[Los Angeles Times Book Prize]].\n*2017 The Bread and Roses Hall of Fame award<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bread and Roses Hall of Fame award |url=https://www.breadandrosesheritage.org/award |website=Bread and Roses Heritage Committee |accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*2010 ''Freedom Summer'' Top 100 Books of the Year, [[The San Francisco Chronicle]].\n*2007 ''Sacco and Vanzetti: The Men, The Murders, and The Judgment of Mankind'' Mystery Writers of America Edgar Award nominee, True Fact/Crime category. [[The Washington Post]], Top 10 Books of the Year.\n*2005 ''Bread and Roses: Mills, Migrants, and The Struggle for The American Dream'' [[The New York Public Library]], 25 Books to Remember in 2005.\n*2003 Best Science and Nature Writing ''Sounding the Alarm,'' Smithsonian.\n*2000 ASCAP Deems Taylor Music Writing Award, ''Concerto for Pencilina and Sewer Flute,'' Smithsonian.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/black-like-me-50-years-later-74543463/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/worlds-unlikeliest-bestseller-81732187/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/the-mad-potter-of-biloxi-106065115/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/big-107619049/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/george-catlins-obsession-72840046/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/a-rally-to-remember-62586455/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/rising-sun-60524172/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/crackdown-58818380/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/the-island-of-lost-maps-a-true-story-of-cartographic-crime-52322202/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/the-dogs-of-war-70305141/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/whats-wrong-with-this-picture-69488987/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/welcome-to-jungle-jims-32768155/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/the-judge-who-ruled-baseball-68788790/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/every-dog-wants-to-have-its-day-in-court-30118379/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/the-amazing-author-of-oz-65297206/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/squaring-the-circle-is-no-piece-of-pi-63767392/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/bound-for-glory-104853825/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/a-unique-home-for-cutting-edge-art-1-62669497/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/you-gotta-remember-eels-are-weird-61805112/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/its-more-than-just-a-game-59430919/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/science-makes-a-better-lighthouse-lens-170677431/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/beyond-the-blue-the-art-of-maxfield-parrish-69379616/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/hello-boys-become-an-erector-master-engineer-69147538/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/concerto-for-pencilina-and-sewer-flute-67104985/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/lay-it-up-65231672/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/lets-get-dale-to-play-162301374/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/a-wizards-scribe-155712387/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/when-i-was-your-age-151987801/\n*https://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/jack-london-followed-his-muse-into-the-wild-55565290/\n*https://www.c-span.org/video/?200871-1/sacco-vanzetti\n*https://www.c-span.org/video/?190719-1/bread-roses\n*https://www.c-span.org/video/?294387-1/freedom-summer&buy=\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/president-and-lunatic\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/what-american-slave-fourth-july\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/how-burning-man-got-so-hot\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/node/133030\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/content/no-to-war\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/american-hero-sargent-york\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/summer-our-discontent\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/node/133061\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/node/132754\n*https://www.americanheritage.com/node/133058\n*https://www.joneslibrary.org/778/A-History-of-the-Jones-Library\n*https://www.amherstbulletin.com/Archives/2014/07/01artwatson-hg-080114\n*http://brucewatsonwriter.com/\n*https://writeanglesconference.com/2011/10/05/an-interview-with-bruce-watson/\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watson, Bruce}}\n\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Attic:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruce_Watson_(writer)"}
{"title_page": "Black Sheep (group)", "text_new": "{{short description|American hip hop group}}\n{{otheruses|Black sheep (disambiguation)}}\n{{blpsources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Black Sheep\n| image                 = Black Sheep.jpg\n| caption            = [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]] (left) & Mista Lawnge (right)\n| image_size            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Queens]]/[[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| instrument          = \n| occupation          = \n| years_active        = 1989&ndash;1995 \u2022 2000-02 \u2022 2006-present\n| label               = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]/[[PolyGram]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Showbiz and A.G.]]<br>[[Chi Ali]]<br>[[Native Tongues]]<br>[[The Legion (group)|The Legion]]<br>Zimbabwe Legit\n| current_members     = [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]]<br>Mista Lawnge\n| past_members        = \n}}\n\n'''Black Sheep''' is an American hip hop duo from [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States, composed of [[Dres (rapper)|Andres \"Dres\" Vargas Titus]] and [[Mister Lawnge|William \"Mista Lawnge\" McLean]].<ref name=\"Larkin90\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Nineties Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=First|isbn=0-7535-0427-8|page=48}}</ref> The duo was from New York but met as teenagers in [[Sanford, North Carolina]], where both of their families relocated.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p15849/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Black Sheep: Biography|author=Bush, John|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2009-08-03}}</ref> The group was an affiliate of the [[Native Tongues]], which included the [[Jungle Brothers]], [[A Tribe Called Quest]], and [[De La Soul]]. After getting together in 1989, Black Sheep debuted in 1991 with the hit song \"Flavor of the Month\" and later released its first album, ''[[A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing (Black Sheep album)|A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing]]'', which gained them praise and recognition in the hip-hop community for the album's unique rhythms and intelligent often humorous lyrics.<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> After six years together, Black Sheep disbanded in 1995, citing creative differences.\n\n==Biography==\n===Initial career and break up (1989\u20131995)===\nBlack Sheep was formed in 1989 by Andres \"Dres\" Vargas Titus and William \"Mista Lawnge\" McLean. Black Sheep was the first hip-hop act to appear on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' after the departure of [[Johnny Carson]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0728165/ | work=IMDB | title=The Tonight Show with Jay Leno - Episode #1.2 | date=May 26, 1992}}</ref>\n\n''A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing'' charted three times on the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart in 1992 with \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\" (#9), and \"[[Strobelite Honey]]\" (#1). Black Sheep was also featured on the [[remix]] of [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]]'s single \"Work to Do\" (#8). The group's relationship with its label, Mercury/PolyGram, allowed Dres to establish a boutique label through which he could sign his own acts. Mercury distributed the imprint, which was called One Love, through PolyGram's [[Fontana Distribution|Independent Label Sales]] division rather than PolyGram Group Distribution. However, only one full-length title was ever released, the only album by affiliated act the Legion, titled ''[[Theme + Echo = Krill]]'' (One Love/Mercury/PolyGram Records 124 029), from 1994.\n\nThe group's second album, ''[[Non-Fiction (Black Sheep album)|Non-Fiction]]'', was released later that year.<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> Because of virtually no promotion and a generally poor reception, the album managed only lackluster sales.\n\n===Aftermath===\nDres was featured on the second [[Handsome Boy Modeling School]] album ''[[White People (album)|White People]]'', on the track \"First...and Then.\" In 2006, Dres released an [[online]]-only album titled ''[[8WM/Novakane]]''. ''8WM'' stands for ''Women with Women with Weed with Wine with Me''. According to [[AllHipHop.com]], Mista Lawnge has changed the spelling of his name to Mr. Long.  He also released a solo project called \u201cThe Class of 89\u201d in 2006.  Dres appeared on the 1990s remix of [[Nas]]' February 2007 song \"[[Where Are They Now? (song)|Where are They Now?]]\"\n\nIn 2008, the single \"[[The Choice is Yours (Revisited)]]\" was ranked number #73 on VH1's 100 Greatest Hip Hop Songs. The song was featured in a commercial for the 2010 [[Kia Soul]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2010/05/kia-soul-commercial-brings-back-the-hamsters-and-the-funk/1 | work=USA Today | title=Kia Soul ad brings back the hamsters, and the funk | date=May 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\" |Album information\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing (Black Sheep album)|A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing]]''\n*Released: October 22, 1991\n*[[RIAA Certification]]: Gold\n*Billboard 200 chart position: #30\n*R&B/Hip-Hop chart position: #15\n*Singles: \"Flavor of the Month\"/\"Butt...In the Meantime\", \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\"/\"The Choice Is Yours\"/\"Have U.N.E. Pull\"/\"Yes\", \"Strobelite Honey\"/\"Gimme the Finga\", \"Similak Child\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Non-Fiction (Black Sheep album)|Non-Fiction]]''\n*Released: December 6, 1994\n*Billboard 200 chart position: #107\n*R&B/Hip-Hop chart position: #24\n*Singles: \"Without a Doubt\"/\"We Boys\", \"North South East West\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[8WM/Novakane]]''\n*Released: October 23, 2006\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[From the Black Pool of Genius]]''\n*Released: June 29, 2010\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Tortured Soul''\n*Released: August 10, 2018\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles and EPs===\n* \"Flavor of the Month\" (1991)\n* \"Flash's theme <small>(remix)</small>\" on ''[[Flash Gordon (soundtrack)#Track listing|Flash Gordon]]'' reissue (Sept 1991)\n* \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\" (Oct 1991)\n**covered by several artists including [[Trik Turner]], [[Bloodhound Gang]], and the [[Deftones]]\n**(Used in the 2010 Kia Soul \"Rapping Hamsters\" commercial)\n* \"Strobelite Honey\" (1992)\n* \"Similak Child\" (1992)\n* \"Without a Doubt\" (1994)\n* \"North South East West\" (1995)\n* ''Redlight, Greenlight'' (EP) (recorded 2000, released 2002)\n\n===Music videos===\n* Black Sheep - Flavor of the Month (1991)\n* Black Sheep - The Choice Is Yours (1991)\n* Black Sheep - Strobelite Honey (1992)\n* [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]] ft. Black Sheep - [[Work to Do]] (Remix) (1992)\n* Showbiz & A.G ft. Black Sheep - Bounce Ta This (1992)\n* Black Sheep - Similak Child (1992)\n* The Legion featuring Dres - Jingle Jangle (1993)\n* Black Sheep - Without a Doubt (1994)\n* Black sheep - Work to DO\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.latinrapper.com/featurednews53.html Dres of Black Sheep interview]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/blacksheep Dres of Black Sheep on Myspace.com]\n*[http://www.mrlongmusic.com Mr. Long's (formerly Mista Lawnge) Solo site]\n*[http://halftimeonline.net/portfolio/black-sheep/ Last Black Sheep Interview as group]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black Sheep}}\n[[Category:American musical duos]]\n[[Category:Hip hop duos]]\n[[Category:Hip hop groups from New York City]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1995]]\n[[Category:Native Tongues Posse]]\n[[Category:People from Sanford, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American hip hop group}}\n{{otheruses2|Black sheep (disambiguation)}}\n{{blpsources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Black Sheep\n| image                 = Black Sheep.jpg\n| caption            = [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]] (left) & Mista Lawnge (right)\n| image_size            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Queens]]/[[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| instrument          = \n| occupation          = \n| years_active        = 1989&ndash;1995 \u2022 2000-02 \u2022 2006-present\n| label               = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]/[[PolyGram]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Showbiz and A.G.]]<br>[[Chi Ali]]<br>[[Native Tongues]]<br>[[The Legion (group)|The Legion]]<br>Zimbabwe Legit\n| current_members     = [[Dres (rapper)|Dres]]<br>Mista Lawnge\n| past_members        = \n}}\n\n'''Black Sheep''' is an American hip hop duo from [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States, composed of [[Dres (rapper)|Andres \"Dres\" Vargas Titus]] and [[Mister Lawnge|William \"Mista Lawnge\" McLean]].<ref name=\"Larkin90\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Nineties Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=First|isbn=0-7535-0427-8|page=48}}</ref> The duo was from New York but met as teenagers in [[Sanford, North Carolina]], where both of their families relocated.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p15849/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Black Sheep: Biography|author=Bush, John|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2009-08-03}}</ref> The group was an affiliate of the [[Native Tongues]], which included the [[Jungle Brothers]], [[A Tribe Called Quest]], and [[De La Soul]]. After getting together in 1989, Black Sheep debuted in 1991 with the hit song \"Flavor of the Month\" and later released its first album, ''[[A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing (Black Sheep album)|A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing]]'', which gained them praise and recognition in the hip-hop community for the album's unique rhythms and intelligent often humorous lyrics.<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> After six years together, Black Sheep disbanded in 1995, citing creative differences.\n\n==Biography==\n===Initial career and break up (1989\u20131995)===\nBlack Sheep was formed in 1989 by Andres \"Dres\" Vargas Titus and William \"Mista Lawnge\" McLean. Black Sheep was the first hip-hop act to appear on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' after the departure of [[Johnny Carson]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0728165/ | work=IMDB | title=The Tonight Show with Jay Leno - Episode #1.2 | date=May 26, 1992}}</ref>\n\n''A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing'' charted three times on the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart in 1992 with \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\" (#9), and \"[[Strobelite Honey]]\" (#1). Black Sheep was also featured on the [[remix]] of [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]]'s single \"Work to Do\" (#8). The group's relationship with its label, Mercury/PolyGram, allowed Dres to establish a boutique label through which he could sign his own acts. Mercury distributed the imprint, which was called One Love, through PolyGram's [[Fontana Distribution|Independent Label Sales]] division rather than PolyGram Group Distribution. However, only one full-length title was ever released, the only album by affiliated act the Legion, titled ''[[Theme + Echo = Krill]]'' (One Love/Mercury/PolyGram Records 124 029), from 1994.\n\nThe group's second album, ''[[Non-Fiction (Black Sheep album)|Non-Fiction]]'', was released later that year.<ref name=\"Larkin90\"/> Because of virtually no promotion and a generally poor reception, the album managed only lackluster sales.\n\n===Aftermath===\nDres was featured on the second [[Handsome Boy Modeling School]] album ''[[White People (album)|White People]]'', on the track \"First...and Then.\" In 2006, Dres released an [[online]]-only album titled ''[[8WM/Novakane]]''. ''8WM'' stands for ''Women with Women with Weed with Wine with Me''. According to [[AllHipHop.com]], Mista Lawnge has changed the spelling of his name to Mr. Long.  He also released a solo project called \u201cThe Class of 89\u201d in 2006.  Dres appeared on the 1990s remix of [[Nas]]' February 2007 song \"[[Where Are They Now? (song)|Where are They Now?]]\"\n\nIn 2008, the single \"[[The Choice is Yours (Revisited)]]\" was ranked number #73 on VH1's 100 Greatest Hip Hop Songs. The song was featured in a commercial for the 2010 [[Kia Soul]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2010/05/kia-soul-commercial-brings-back-the-hamsters-and-the-funk/1 | work=USA Today | title=Kia Soul ad brings back the hamsters, and the funk | date=May 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\" |Album information\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing (Black Sheep album)|A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing]]''\n*Released: October 22, 1991\n*[[RIAA Certification]]: Gold\n*Billboard 200 chart position: #30\n*R&B/Hip-Hop chart position: #15\n*Singles: \"Flavor of the Month\"/\"Butt...In the Meantime\", \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\"/\"The Choice Is Yours\"/\"Have U.N.E. Pull\"/\"Yes\", \"Strobelite Honey\"/\"Gimme the Finga\", \"Similak Child\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Non-Fiction (Black Sheep album)|Non-Fiction]]''\n*Released: December 6, 1994\n*Billboard 200 chart position: #107\n*R&B/Hip-Hop chart position: #24\n*Singles: \"Without a Doubt\"/\"We Boys\", \"North South East West\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[8WM/Novakane]]''\n*Released: October 23, 2006\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[From the Black Pool of Genius]]''\n*Released: June 29, 2010\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Tortured Soul''\n*Released: August 10, 2018\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles and EPs===\n* \"Flavor of the Month\" (1991)\n* \"Flash's theme <small>(remix)</small>\" on ''[[Flash Gordon (soundtrack)#Track listing|Flash Gordon]]'' reissue (Sept 1991)\n* \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\" (Oct 1991)\n**covered by several artists including [[Trik Turner]], [[Bloodhound Gang]], and the [[Deftones]]\n**(Used in the 2010 Kia Soul \"Rapping Hamsters\" commercial)\n* \"Strobelite Honey\" (1992)\n* \"Similak Child\" (1992)\n* \"Without a Doubt\" (1994)\n* \"North South East West\" (1995)\n* ''Redlight, Greenlight'' (EP) (recorded 2000, released 2002)\n\n===Music videos===\n* Black Sheep - Flavor of the Month (1991)\n* Black Sheep - The Choice Is Yours (1991)\n* Black Sheep - Strobelite Honey (1992)\n* [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]] ft. Black Sheep - [[Work to Do]] (Remix) (1992)\n* Showbiz & A.G ft. Black Sheep - Bounce Ta This (1992)\n* Black Sheep - Similak Child (1992)\n* The Legion featuring Dres - Jingle Jangle (1993)\n* Black Sheep - Without a Doubt (1994)\n* Black sheep - Work to DO\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.latinrapper.com/featurednews53.html Dres of Black Sheep interview]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/blacksheep Dres of Black Sheep on Myspace.com]\n*[http://www.mrlongmusic.com Mr. Long's (formerly Mista Lawnge) Solo site]\n*[http://halftimeonline.net/portfolio/black-sheep/ Last Black Sheep Interview as group]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black Sheep}}\n[[Category:American musical duos]]\n[[Category:Hip hop duos]]\n[[Category:Hip hop groups from New York City]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1995]]\n[[Category:Native Tongues Posse]]\n[[Category:People from Sanford, North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed broken hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Sheep_(group)"}
{"title_page": "1992 United States presidential election in Alaska", "text_new": "{{Main|1992 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1992 [[United States presidential election]] in Alaska\n| country = Alaska\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1988 United States presidential election in Alaska\n| previous_year = 1988\n| next_election = 1996 United States presidential election in Alaska\n| next_year = 1996\n| election_date = November 3, 1992\n| image_size = x160px\n| image1 = George H. W. Bush presidential portrait (cropped 2).jpg\n| nominee1 = '''[[George H. W. Bush]]''' \n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Dan Quayle]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''3'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''102,000'''\n| percentage1 = '''39.46%'''\t\n| image2 = Bill Clinton.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Arkansas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Al Gore]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 78,294\n| percentage2 = 30.29%\t\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 73,481\t   \n| percentage3 = 28.43%\n| map_image = AK1992.jpg\n| map_size = 300px\n| map_caption = Borough Results\n{{legend|#f2b3be|Bush-40-50%}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{ElectionsAK}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Alaska''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose three representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Alaska]] was won by incumbent President [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Texas]]) with 39.4% of the popular vote over Governor [[Bill Clinton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Arkansas]]) with 30.2%. Bush won Alaska by a margin of 9.2%. Businessman [[Ross Perot]] ([[Independent (politician)|I]]-Texas) finished in third, with 28.4% of the popular vote.<ref name=results/> Clinton ultimately won the national vote, defeating incumbent President Bush. Alaska has only voted Democratic once, and that was in [[1964 United States presidential election in Alaska|1964]] for [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]. <ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> It was also the last time a Republican only won the state of Alaska by a single digit margin of victory.\n\nWith 28.43% of the popular vote, Alaska would prove to be Perot's second strongest state after [[1992 United States presidential election in Maine|Maine]]. Alaska was also one of seven states to give a county to Perot. The others being [[1992_United_States_presidential_election_in_California|California]], [[1992_United_States_presidential_election_in_Colorado|Colorado]], [[1992_United_States_presidential_election_in_Kansas|Kansas]], Maine, [[1992_United_States_presidential_election_in_Nevada|Nevada]] and [[1992_United_States_presidential_election_in_Texas|Texas]]. Alaska awarded Perot [[Denali_Borough,_Alaska|Denali Borough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/stats.php?year=1992&f=0&off=0&elect=0|title=1992 Presidential Election Statistics|publisher=Dave Leip\u2019s Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|date= |accessdate=2018-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; bo